<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe: Traitors Must Go </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Friday said there is an open rebellion against his ruling
ZANU (PF) by some top party leaders including mps and Speaker
Cyril Ndebele, the Zimbabwe National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address at the start of the 33rd session of the
party's central committee, Mugabe said these ''evil schemers,
conspirators, political saboteurs'' and their ''misguided''
ambitions were responsible for the present situation of confusion
and anxiety in ZANU (PF) and have to be ''dealt with once and for
all.''
</P>
<P>
''Let us begin to fish them out and expose them for what they
are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said there were some mps in the 150-strong ZANU
(PF)-dominated legislative assembly who had virtually become
independent members, believing they had unrestricted freedom to
adopt and propound any ideas of their choice, even if these went
against their party.
</P>
<P>
''It is indeed a case of arrogant defiance of the party and
its leadership. It is a rebellion itself which such members are
engaged in,'' said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
''Alas, we notice also an even more strange phenomenon. The
speaker, the honorable speaker, has decided to join in the
rebellion against the party as he and those in collusion with him
seek to stultify it in its political and administrative role to
discipline its own members. What rank madness has gripped some of
us, i ask?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Departing briefly from his prepared speech, he said an
hour-long impromptu meeting of highest decision-maing body of the
party, the politburo, had already taken a decision on the fate of
the speaker and others deemed to have become rebels.
</P>
<P>
A disciplinary committee of ZANU (PF) this week summoned
Masvingo central mp Dzikamayi Mavhaire to explain statements he
made in parliament when he recently introduced a motion on
constitutional reform in which he was quoted as saying that
Mugabe ''must go''.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe stressed that mps at all times had the duty and
obligation to admit and recognize that their membership of
parliament arose from their sponsorship by ZANU (PF) and,
therefore, they must remain accountable to it for their
performance in parliament, as they must also remain accountable,
but in a secondary manner, to the constituency they represented.
</P>
<P>
''Several of our members are no longer paying any heed to the
views or position of the party and government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said ordinary members of the party who were solidly
behind the party and its leadership were pleading for remedial
action that would ensure its unity and viability and the success
of the party and government programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
