<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Selects New Executive for China Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 19 (Xinhua) -- Boeing has selected a
41-year-old executive to lead its all-important China operations.
</P>
<P>
Raymond Bracy will assume the presidency of Boeing China
Inc. next month. A former U.S. Navy pilot and Harvard MBA, Bracy
has been with Boeing's Commercial Airplane Group since 1989 and is
one of the youngest executives ever chosen by Boeing for such a
high-level post.
</P>
<P>
He is replacing Michael Zimmerman, who held the post for four
years and is retiring.
</P>
<P>
Boeing is forecasting a market for approximately 1,900
commercial jet aircraft sales in China worth 124 billion
U.S. dollars over the next 20 years, making China the largest
forecasted aviation market outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
Bracy met many of China's airline officials in his former job
as director of business management and deputy vice president for
Boeing's Asia-Pacific region. He told the Seattle Times that his
role will involve more diplomatic aspects than day-to-day
operations.
</P>
<P>
He said his goal will be to build and maintain Boeing's
reputation as a quality supplier with outstanding service.
</P>
<P>
"We're going to make sure we preserve our market share," he
said, acknowledging that Airbus Industrie will continue to compete
with Boeing for China orders.
</P>
<P>
Boeing now works with 20 of the 34 jet-operating airlines in
China. Through December 31, 1997, 288 of 400 jetliners operating
in China were made by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing market share in China is 72 percent, according to
the company.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, Bracy will direct an office staff of 47 and about
150 Boeing employees overall who work in 21 cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Bracy is different from a lot of Boeing executives who are
specialists in a single field. He is not just a salesman or an
engineer. He is knowledgeable about the inner workings of the
aviation business, manufacturing airplanes and flying them.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said these qualities helped him won the appointment
amid fierce inside competition.
</P>
<P>
Bracy believes that his calm approach is one of the main
reasons why he was chosen for the job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
