<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Accuses Foreign Missions of Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has again accused
diplomatic missions of financing pro-democracy and dissident
activities in the country, following alleged foreign support for
last year's foiled coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi Thursday alleged that the recent
upsurge in "dissident activities" particularly in Lagos by some
pro-democracy activists have the financial and other support of
some diplomatic missions.
</P>
<P>
It is noted that the minister was referring to the
five-million-man rally in Lagos early this week to oppose the
presidential candidacy of the head of state General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The rally was dispersed by armed police before it really
started, while another two-million-man pro-Abacha rally held in
the capital of Abuja boasted a success under heavy security
protection.
</P>
<P>
According to Ikimi, the matter "is being investigated just as
the case of those missions which gave support to the coup
plotters in December 1997."
</P>
<P>
Ikimi said that the 3.4 million U.S. Dollars European
Parliament approved two weeks ago to support non-government
organizations for poverty alleviation in Nigeria was meant to
finance anti-government activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to assure the European Union that the latest attempt
like others they embarked upon in the past to fund clandestine
political organizations and dissidents will also fail," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
In a veiled attempt to link pro-democracy activities and the
presence of the foreign missions in Lagos, Ikimi gave the
missions an ultimatum to relocate to the capital Abuja before the
end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Failure to do so, the government "will stop further
transactions with missions in Lagos by that date," he added.
</P>
<P>
Since the Nigerian government moved to Abuja eight years ago,
it has kept asking foreign missions to move. However, only nine
foreign missions have done so, with most of them still in Lagos,
the former capital.
</P>
<P>
According to observers, Ikimi's accusation followed statements
by the United States which said the U.S. government will not
accept Abacha as the country's next civilian president, scheduled
to inaugurate on October 1 this year at the end of the three-year
transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright also said Thursday that her government was expecting "a
real transition, not phony or cosmetic one" in Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
