<HEADLINE> 42 Bodies Recovered from Crash Site of Afghan Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Rescue workers have recovered
42 bodies from the crash site of an Afghan airliner which crashed
Thursday near the Afghan capital of Kabul, said reports reaching
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
All 45, including 13 crew and 32 passengers, on board the
Boeing 727 operated by Afghanistan's Ariana airline were killed
when the jet crashed into a mountain in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers found the wreckage of the plane about 100 meters
below the summit of Sharki Baratayi, about 15 kilometers south of
Kabul, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
However, the rescuers have not found the black box of the
aircraft because their efforts were hampered by mines left over
from the war that followed the soviet invasion of Afghanistan in
1979.
</P>
<P>
An Ariana official at the site said the plane, which was on its
way from the Afghan southwestern city of Kandahar to Kabul,
crashed at 2:00 p.m. (1030 GMT) Thursday as it hit a bank of
cloud, rain and sleet near the capital, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Ariana, operating regular services only to some Gulf cities,
was hit recently by a series of serious accidents. In January, an
Antonov 32 plane on a domestic route crashed in bad weather on
Pakistani soil, killing all 80 on board.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a Tupolev jet crashed on a training flight in the
Afghanistan's eastern city of Jalalabad, killing five crew
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
