<HEADLINE> German Activists Protest Nuclear Waste Shipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 20 (Xinhua) -- About 2,500 Germany anti-nuclear
activists gathered in Ahaus Friday to protest against a nuclear
waste shipment.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 protesters defying a police ban on demonstrations had
been detained, according to German media report.
</P>
<P>
The controversial shipment of six containers of nuclear waste
was due to a storage depot in Ahaus near the Dutch border.
</P>
<P>
Police said so far demonstrations had been peaceful and there
had been no violent clashes.
</P>
<P>
But shortly after leaving a depot in Baden-wuerttemberg, the
train hauling the nuclear waste was delayed when three
anti-nuclear activists chained themselves to the tracks.
</P>
<P>
Several thousand policemen were involved in the security
operation to protect the latest nuclear waste transport which
started on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A German policeman was struck by a train and died of head
injuries Friday morning hours before the special train carrying
nuclear waste from two southern German nuclear power plants was
due to pass a site near Wuersburg.
</P>
<P>
Another policeman was also injured Friday morning after being
struck by a car that refused to stop for a security control post
near Ahaus.
</P>
<P>
A similar transport carrying six nuclear waste containers last
year required 30,000 police to provide protection and cost the
government nearly 61 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Anti-nuclear activists have called on the government to close
all nuclear power plants in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
