<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Draw Private Cash to Modernize Tube </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The British government announced a
plan Friday to draw private investment into the infrastructure of
London's Underground network.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott told the House of Commons
that private firms were to be given a role in running London's
Tube, although this was not privatization of the system and its
assets would remain in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
"It is not privatization, nor nationalization, but a radical
new `third way' to generate investment while retaining a
publicly-owned, publicly accountable network," Prescott said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "The freehold ownership of assets will remain in the
public sector. The private sector contractor or contractors will
be free to borrow sums outside the constraints of the public
sector pay round."
</P>
<P>
He also announced 365 million pounds (584 million U.S. dollars)
of investment over the next two years so that the tube would be
"returned to the people."
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, contractors will be responsible for
refurbishing stations, replacing tracks, upgrading signaling and
refurbishing or replacing trains, as well as regular maintenance.
</P>
<P>
But the London Underground company will still be responsible
for operating services, including ticketing, fares, service levels
and the operation of the signalling system and safety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
