<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus' trade gap widened further in 1997, as
imports increased by more than 2 percent while exports continued
to decline.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Statistics Department released Friday said
total imports last year rose to 1,898 million Cyprus pounds
(about 3,796 million U.S. dollars), up 2.2 percent over 1996 of
1,858 million pounds (about 3,716 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Total exports amounted to 639 million pounds (about 1,278
million dollars), showing a decline of 1.5 percent over the 1996
figure of 649 million pounds (about 1,298 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decline was mainly due to a 4.1 percent fall in domestic
exports, which amounted to 213 million pounds (about 426 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade deficit for the year widened to
1,259 million pounds (about 2,518 million dollars) compared to
1,208 million pounds (about 2,416 million dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Oil revenues of the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
dropped to 14.7 billion dollars in 1997 from 15.5 billion dollars
in 1996, Dubai Crown Prince Sheikh Mohamed Bin Rashid Al Maktoum
said Thursday in Dubai.
</P>
<P>
He said that the UAE economy had become more flexible in
response to the current changes in international oil markets.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the UAE had succeeded in making a big stride
in the field of socio-economic development and the diversification
of the sources of national income.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Cairo will host the 36th conference of the
International Advertising Society on May 10-13, Egyptian press
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 officials and businessmen from 90 countries will
participate in the conference which will be inaugurated by
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
