<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Retail Trade Dips in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Canadian retail sales declined 1.9
percent to 19.8 billion dollars (13.9 billion U.S. dollars) in
January, Statistics Canada said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The January ice storm in parts of Quebec, Ontario and New
Brunswick provinces and the resulting power outages resulted in a
disruption of sales in some sectors.
</P>
<P>
In addition, motor and recreational vehicle sales posted a
large decrease after a significant increase in December, the
statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decline, the level of retail sales in January was
5.1 percent higher than the same month in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Canada's retail sales have generally been rising since the
start of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the rate of increase has been slowing in recent months,
after a period of strong advances from the fall of 1996 to the
fall of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
