<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harare People Demonstrate to Support Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Several hundred people, mostly
women, thronged the ruling Zanu (PF) party headquarters here
Friday in show of support for President Robert Mugabe before the
central committee of his deeply-divided party meets.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration organized by the party's Harare province and
the Zimbabwe national liberation war veterans association saw
more than a thousand placard-waving supporters chanting
pro-Mugabe slogans and singing revolutionary songs, the Zimbabwe
National News Agency Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
Messages on the placards denounced Secretary-General of the
Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions Morgan Tsvangirayi, praised
Mugabe's hard-line stance on the land reform issue and proclaimed
support for his continued leadership.
</P>
<P>
The labor movement has become the biggest challenge to the
government, having successfully organized two nationwide strikes
to protest a sharply-rising cost of living and unpopular
government taxes.
</P>
<P>
Some placards also denounced the party's Masvingo provincial
Chairman Dzikamayi Mavhaire, currently facing disciplinary
inquiry into utterances he made in parliament in which he was
quoted as calling on Mugabe to step down.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the demonstrators, Mugabe shied from naming
Mavhaire as a divisive element within the party, but only
mentioned the deep divisions in the party's Masvingo, Manicaland
and Mashonaland West provinces.
</P>
<P>
There are 10 provinces in Zimbabwe now.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, "they are saying that the next congress is too
far away and they want to grab power without going through
congress."
</P>
<P>
He said the party should learn to resolve its contradictions
through debate, but acknowledged that there would always be
people within the party who are opposed to his leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
