<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contact Group Leaders Keep Up Pressure on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Political directors from the
United States, France, Italy, Britain, Germany and Russia Friday
met here to keep up the pressure on both Serbia and ethnic
Albanian leaders in Kosovo to open talks aimed at ending recent
violence in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The six-nation Contact Group met in Brussels to discuss whether
Yugoslavia had done enough to avoid the threat of international
sanctions in retaliation for its repression in the province.
</P>
<P>
British political director Jeremy Greenstock, who chaired the
meeting Friday, told reporters that there was slight progress from
both sides on the Kosovo dispute but it was still far from meeting
"all the (group's) requirements."
</P>
<P>
Ministers from the Contact Group are scheduled to meet in Bonn
next Wednesday. Greenstock said it would continue to put pressure
on both sides to move towards a dialogue without preconditions.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see no violence in Kosovo; we want to see correct
standards of policing; we want to see both sides moving towards
dialogue; and we want to see access for all international
organizations, non-governmental organizations, the Red Cross,
diplomats, as well as journalists," he said.
</P>
<P>
A 10-day deadline, which expired Thursday, had been set earlier
this month for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to withdraw
his special police and start talking to the ethnic Albanians who
make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population.
</P>
<P>
Serb special police units have been involved in a bloody
crackdown in Kosovo this month in which at least 80 people have
been killed.
</P>
<P>
There have been recently signs of disagreement on the need for
sanctions between members of the Contact Group, but no one leaving
the meeting would comment on this.
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats have said Milosevic is trying to drive a
wedge between Russia and its five Western Contact Group partners
in a bid to avert tougher international action.
</P>
<P>
The Albanians, demanding international mediation and
independence, or at least autonomy within Yugoslavia, have
boycotted Serbian government negotiators in Kosovo for almost a
week, though Kosovo's Albanian leaders admitted Friday that this
tactic was losing international credibility.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people Friday staged a protest outside the British
mission building in Brussels where the political leaders met.
</P>
<P>
They held banners which read "stop the ethnic cleansing," "stop
the genocide" and Kosovo's "divorce from the devil." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
