<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Welcomes EU Concessions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 20 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has welcomed
the latest tariff concessions by the European Union (EU) in their
trade negotiations for a free trade agreement, local media
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The EU recently offered to include 510 more South African
exports in its tariff-free list, including about 30 industrial
products and 480 farm goods from ferro-alloys, wines to dairy
products.
</P>
<P>
But South Africa was disappointed that the new concessions did
not affect any of the "sensitive" products, mainly agricultural
goods, said South Africa's chief trade negotiator with the EU,
Elias Links Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa would make no more concessions until Europe
changed its original mandate which excluded about 45 percent of
South Africa's farm products, the mainstay of its exports to
Europe, from a proposed free trade area, Links said.
</P>
<P>
At a conference at the South African Institute of
International Affairs Thursday, Links said the new offer would
help to push the EU's list of tariff-free products to just over
94 percent of South African imports from its January offer of 90
percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the signs of flexibility had lent hope that a
free-trade area agreement could be nailed down by the target date
of the middle of this year. The two sides had been engaged in
talks for more than 31 months.
</P>
<P>
Links, the ambassador to the EU, criticized the EU for
reducing tariffs at a slower pace than South Africa. He said it
contradicted a previous agreement in principle that the EU would
lower barriers faster than South Africa.
</P>
<P>
South Africa increased its list of tariff-free products from
about 55 percent to about 81 percent in its last offer late last
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The goal is for South Africa to allow tariff-free entry of 85
percent of EU goods and for the EU to allow 95 percent of South
African goods. This would produce an average of 90 percent, which
would meet the free trade criteria of the World Trade
Organization, Links said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
