<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Lower House Passes FY '98 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives (lower
house) approved the 77.67 trillion yen (about 606.8 billion dollars)
national budget for fiscal 1998 Friday.
</P>
<P>
The budget for the year starting April 1 was passed at a lower
house plenary session with the backing of members of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and its two noncabinet allies -- the
Social Democratic Party (SDP) and the New Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The budget was immediately sent to the House of Councillors (upper
house) which is expected to start deliberations on it next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Even if the upper house fails to agree on the budget, it will be
automatically enacted April 19.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Constitution stipulates that if the upper house fails to
take final action within 30 days after the budget's passage through
the lower house, the lower house's decision will be the parliamentary
decision.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal 1998 budget is the first compiled under restraints of
the fiscal rehabilitation law and is only 0.4 percent larger than the
initial fiscal 1997 budget.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders welcomed the lower house's nod to the budget and
urged that it pass through the Diet (parliament) as early as
possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
