<HEADLINE> French Top Ballet Troupe to Be on First Tour in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- France's top ballet troupe, Ballet
de l'Opera de Paris, will be on its first tour to China from April
11 to 13, said Brigitte Lefevre, director of dance of the Opera de
Paris, Friday.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-five dancers of the ballet troupe, including seven
stars, will perform in the Great Hall of the People in Beijing for
some 33,000 spectators, said Lefevre at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The ballet troupe was invited by the Chinese government when
President Jacques Chirac visited China in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
The troupe will present a unique program "witnessing the
diversity of the great Western classic repertoire" with romantic
dances such as "Giselle" of Coralli and Perrot which was created
by the troupe in 1841, said Lefevre.
</P>
<P>
They will perform extracts from "Raymonda," in the version
adopted by the late Russian dancer Rudolf Nureyev after Petipa,
"the Great Classic Step" of Victor Gsovsky and "Brilliant Allegro"
of George Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
The stars who will go to China are Laurent Hilaire, Nicolas Le
Riche and Manuel Legris -- all of whom will dance as the prince in
"Giselle," and Kader Belarbi, who will dance "Brilliant Allegro,"
Isabelle Guerin, Elisabeth Platel, and Elisabeth Maurin.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges between Ballet de l'Operat de Paris and China
dated back to 1980, when its former star Lycette Darsonval visited
the Beijing Central Ballet, and some of its dancers visited
Shanghai in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The Ballets de l'Operat de Lyon and the Ballet de l'Opera du
Rhin of France have already visited China at the invitation of the
Chinese government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
