<HEADLINE> Ottawa to Host Mine Workshop Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Canada will host a two-day
workshop here next week to coordinate support for the mine action
agenda resulting from last December's conference.
</P>
<P>
During that conference, 122 countries signed a treaty, pledging
to eliminate anti-personal landmines.
</P>
<P>
"Now that we have a treaty, the anti-personal mine campaign
focus shifts to the immediate priorities of maintaining the
political will to implement the convention and coordinate mine
action activities," said Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
In the workshop, senior experts from donor and mine-affected
countries, multilateral agencies and non-government organizations
are expected to discuss ways to promote partnerships that will
eliminate duplication of activities.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to ensure the most effective use of the financial
resources pledged by donor countries during last December's Ottawa
conference, the government said in a news release Friday.
</P>
<P>
Since the conference, two more countries have signed the
treaty. So far, six countries, including Canada, have ratified the
document, the release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
