<HEADLINE> UK Rural Dwellers Enjoy Better Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- People living in the countryside
in Britain enjoy better life than those city dwellers, having
better jobs and health, bigger houses and more cars, according to
an official study Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said in its quarterly
journal Population Trends that rural lifestyles retain advantages
over urban living in many ways.
</P>
<P>
It said that Britain's rural population remained stable at 10
percent of the whole population between the censuses of 1981 and
1991.
</P>
<P>
Country people are strikingly healthier, with only 10.1 percent
of people in English rural areas reporting a long-term illness,
compared with 12.2 percent of those in towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 40 percent of those rural households have
two or more cars, nearly twice the proportion in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Those rural homes which are detached houses amount to 50
percent, compared with just 16.7 percent in urban areas, and rural
homes have an average of 5.9 rooms against 5.0 in urban homes.
</P>
<P>
The study added that one in three households in English rural
areas is headed by someone with a professional or managerial job,
compared with fewer than one in four of their urban counterparts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-20 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Hopes Resolution 425 to Be Implemented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday expressed the hope that the
U.N. resolution 425, which calls for an unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon, will be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the expression at a joint news conference with
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz after they held talks on
regional issues, especially the issue of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said that attention should be also given to the interests
of the two parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that many things in the world have happened
since the U.N. adopted the resolution, stressing that these
changes should be taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
Annan also called on the parties concerned to take necessary
steps to implement the resolution 425 which was adopted in 1978
after Israeli first invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was not a mediator in the Middle East peace
process, adding that only the United States carried out the
mediation mission among the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Boueiz said that his talks with Annan also touched
on the Lebanese detainees held in Israeli prisons and Palestinian
refugees in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed his refusal to let the 360,000 Palestinian
refugees living in Lebanon to settle in his country. The refugees
are also not allowed to work in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here from Egypt Friday on the third leg of his
first Middle East tour since he took office in January 1997. The
trip has taken him to Jordan and will also take him to Syria,
Israel and Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit to Lebanon, Annan will also meet with
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and House Speaker Nabih Berri
on Friday and President Elias Hrawi on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Beirut International Airport, he was
greeted by Lebanese officials as well as a crowd of Lebanese
whose sons or husbands are being detained in Israeli prisons.
</P>
<P>
They handed Annan a letter welcoming him to visit Lebanon
and calling on him to impose pressure on Israel to release their
relatives.
</P>
<P>
Annan promised to press Israel to permit the International Red
Cross staff to enter Israeli prisons.
</P>
<P>
Some 210 Lebanese are being held in Israeli prisons inside
Israeli territory and in south Lebanon reportedly because of their
 refusal to collaborate with Israeli occupying forces or having
connections with Hezbollah (Party of God), the country's leading
military group against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Israel is still occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer area in
south Lebanon since it declared the area as a buffer zone in
1985 to protect its northern villages and towns from Hezbollah
cross-border attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
