<HEADLINE> Greece, Cyprus to Strengthen Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Cyprus Friday agreed to
further strengthen their cooperation on matters of armaments,
military exercises and training in order to safeguard the island
republic's security after the talks between the defense ministers
of the two countries took place here.
</P>
<P>
They also decided to meet regularly in order to take any
additional measures required to attain the common objectives.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their lengthy talks, Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said that they would do everything possible to
ensure "the greatest possible sense of security" on Cyprus within
the framework of the joint strategy of Greece and Hellenism.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Cyprus Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou, who
arrived here Thursday for a two-day official visit, said that the
two countries would help each other to make sure the vital
interests of Hellenism for peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers shared the view that Cyprus' entry into the
European Union (EU) would enhance the island's position in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Omirou also met with Greek Foreign
Undersecretary Yiannos Kranidiotis, who warned that there would be
difficulties along the process of Cyprus' accession to the EU,
which would require alertness and cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive coup
backed by Athens.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus's accession negotiations with the EU will start as
scheduled on March 31, but northern Cyprus and Turkey have
expressed their opposition to such a move by Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
