<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Warns against Political Schism in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Iran's State
Expediency Council and former Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani
Friday warned against political schism in the country, urging
people to respect political etiquette.
</P>
<P>
"Freedoms, debates, arguments, and positive criticisms are good
things, without which a society will not go forward, but those
things must not be allowed to cause schism between our people and
divide them," Rafsanjani said at the Friday prayers congregation
in the shrine of the late Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Musavi
Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani made the remarks in response to a growing tension
between the left-wing and right-wing political groups. They
accused each other of breaking the country's laws.
</P>
<P>
A physical fighting even happened in the Majlis or parliament
between rival representatives on Wednesday when a right-wing
legislator tried to slap Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri,
who was summoned to the Majlis to explain why the Interior
Ministry issued permit for a mourning ceremony for Mehdi
Bazargan, the late leader of Iran's opposition group the Freedom
Movement of Iran (FMI).
</P>
<P>
The hard-line factions also demanded to impeach Nouri after
the Interior Ministry allowed a student group to hold a rally
against a rule of the country's Constitutional Guardians Council
to reject several candidates for the Majlis by-elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the left-wing groups, which supported President
Mohammad Khatami, defended the Interior Ministry's decisions,
calling for more freedom of expression and gatherings.
</P>
<P>
"I hope in the future every person in this country will
demonstrate some form of political etiquette in dealing with the
various issues of the country," because "we have many enemies
here and there around us and they will try to provoke one group
against another," Rafsanjani said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
