<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One-Parent Families Rise in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The total number of one-parent
families in Britain rose by 27 percent from 1.23 million in 1990
to reach 1.56 million in 1995, according to official figures
Friday.
</P>
<P>
A study carried in the quarterly journal, Population Trends, of
the Office for National Statistics said that the 1995 figure is
broadly double the total in the late 1970s and represents more
than one in five families with dependent children.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the study said that in the five years between 1990
and 1995, the number of children living in one-parent families
rose by one-third to reach 2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
It said that the average family size of single, lone mothers,
those who had never married or cohabited, had grown most by 30
percent in the 14 years between 1981 and 1995, followed by that of
separated lone mothers, by 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the rise in lone parents is partly the
result of career women deciding in their 30s that they want to be
mothers.
</P>
<P>
Another reason lies in changing expectations and values. Women
are now less likely to stay in relationships that are not working.
</P>
</TEXT>
