<HEADLINE> Rwanda's Hutu Armed Insurrection Doomed: Kagame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The armed insurgency that has
been causing insecurity in northwestern Rwanda is in its last
days, the Rwandan News Agency (RNA) quoted Rwandan Vice-President
Major General Paul Kagame as claiming.
</P>
<P>
Kagame was addressing over 3,000 residents of Nyabikenke, who
had gathered to celebrate the reopening of the local health
center Thursday that had just been rehabilitated, a special RNA
report sent to Xinhua here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The problems of insecurity have continually given us a
headache since 1994," Kagame, who les as Defense Minister,
admitted.
</P>
<P>
"But the government, in collaboration with security forces,
and the population have stood up and restored security in most
prefectures of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The health center was destroyed during the 1994 genocide by
the same forces that are creating havoc in northwestern Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the reconstruction work on the center is
estimated at around 750,000 U.S. Dollars, donated by the UNICEF
and the Dutch government.
</P>
<P>
General Kagame encouraged the residents of Ndiza to safeguard
infrastructure like this health center, and to shun for ever
divisive politics.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, RNA said the Rwandan army has killed more
than 280 Hutu insurgents in battles in Gitarama province over the
past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
Quoting military sources, it said security had been restored
in almost all the communes attacked by infiltrators and that
operations were continuing to "track down the remnants of these
criminals." 
</P>
