<HEADLINE> China Opposed to Sanctions Against Libya: Qin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- China is not in favor of
sanctions against Libya, which have brought untold sufferings to
the Libyan people, Qin Huasun, Chinese ambassador to the United
Nations, stressed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin made the remarks at the meeting of the Security
Council, which held an open debate on the question of Libya.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the sanctions against Libya have brought sufferings
especially to women and children, undermined the development of
Libya, and at the same time affected economic development of third
countries.
</P>
<P>
Qin said China is gravely concerned about the adverse effects
of the sanctions, and facts have shown sanctions, instead of
solving the problem, only aggravate matters.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said China is in favor of lifting the sanctions
as soon as possible, and China supports the request raised by the
Arab League and the Organization of African Unity on numerous
occasions to lift the sanctions against Libya at an early date.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the U.N. secretary-general recently sent a
fact-finding mission to Libya to look into the negative impacts of
the sanctions, and the report of the mission is basically an
accurate account of the situation there. China is of the view that
the Security Council and its Sanctions Committee should give it a
serious review and take measures to ease the situation, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
