<HEADLINE> More Canadians Use Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- More Canadian families went onto
the information highway last year, especially for those with
higher incomes, said reports Friday.
</P>
<P>
The proportion using the Internet from home "almost doubled" to
13 percent of Canadian households between 1996 and 1997, according
to the latest figures from Statistics Canada.
</P>
<P>
Use of the Internet among families whose incomes were in the
top fifth of all households soared to 26 percent, up from 16.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Though families with incomes in the bottom fifth were slow to
be plugged into the Internet, their use of the technology from
their homes actually increased faster, more than doubling to 5.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The statistics agency also noted that families with children
are more likely to possess a computer.
</P>
<P>
Last year, one half of Canadian families with children under 18
had a computer.
</P>
<P>
A 1994 survey found that 81 percent of young people aged 15 to
24 were able to use a computer, the highest rate for any age
group.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, only one in 10 "elderly" Canadians knew how to
operate a computer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
