<HEADLINE> Tanzania Threatens to Close Refugees Camps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 20 (Xinhua) - Tanzania warned Rwanda and
Burundi Friday it would close the camps for their refugees in
Tanzania if they continue to accuse it of supporting the
so-called refugees' crossing-border attacks on them.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister for Home Affairs Segela Nswima told a press
conference that the accusation by the Rwandan government, which
was aired by the Western media this week, was groundless.
</P>
<P>
"No refugees have crossed the border to Rwanda for attacks,"
he said. "Actually the attacks are in the western part of that
country where we do not share a common border."
</P>
<P>
Nswima said that fed up with endless accusations by the
Rwandan and Burundi governments, Tanzania feels too taxing and
tough to continue the task of caring for their refugees.
</P>
<P>
He said that during her visit to the camps last month, the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako
Ogata refuted the reported claims that there are soldiers in the
refugees camps.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government told the UNHCR head that if the
accusations went from bad to worse, it would definitely close the
camps and repatriate the refugees back to their homelands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a delegation of the envoys based in Dar es Salaam
left Friday for Tanzania's western region of Kigoma to witness
the repatriation of some Congolese refugees, the United Nations
officials said.
</P>
<P>
During their two-day visit, jointly organized by the offices
of the UNHCR and the World Food Program (WFP), the dignitaries
will have a first-hand impression of the difficulties in refugee
assistance program including delivering food, medicine and other
supplies to the refugee camps in the region.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR statistics show that by the end of last year,
Tanzania harbors 346,703 refugees form Burundi, the Democratic
Republic of Congo, Rwanda and Somalia, with the Burundians
accounting for 266,498.
</P>
<P>
Despite the endless civil war in Burundi, there are clear
indications that some 68,000 Burundi refugees had returned home
in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
