<HEADLINE> Kohl, Blair Hail Good Anglo-German Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 20 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and
visiting British Prime Minister Tony Blair Friday expressed
satisfaction about the good relations between the two countries
and stressed that they will continue to cooperate closely in the
future.
</P>
<P>
"The relations between Germany and Britain are strong and are
getting stronger all the time. That is a good thing for both our
countries, as well as Europe and the world," said Blair after a
three-hour meeting with Kohl in Bonn which was held under the
framework of regular Anglo-German consultations.
</P>
<P>
On European issues, both leaders agreed that it was important
to ensure a successful launch of the single European currency euro
and to make progress on the European Union (EU) enlargement and EU
reforms.
</P>
<P>
"There are many difficult obstacles to be overcome, but we are
committed to the same objectives and the same goals," Blair said
at a news conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that although Britain had decided not to join
euro in the first wave in January next year, it would still play a
fully constructive role in launching euro and was fully prepared
for the event.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed a number of international
issues. Both of them agreed that Europe should continue to play a
constructive role in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo crisis, Blair stressed that what had been done by
Europe in stemming an escalation of recent conflicts there was one
of the examples showing that Europe was able to cooperate very
quickly in taking definite action in response to international
problems within its border.
</P>
<P>
Later in the afternoon, Blair held one-hour talks with Gerhard
Schroeder, who will represent Germany's main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) to challenge Kohl in the national elections
due in September this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Schroeder, he and Blair shared the common view
that Europe should spend more on job creation to combat serious
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, who likes to be compared with Blair who led the
leftist British Labor Party to a big election victory last year,
also expressed confidence that the SPD, the German equivalent of
the Labor Party, would also come to power after the September
elections.
</P>
<P>
Blair himself, however, has been cautious enough in Bonn not to
intervene in the German elections.
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters whether Germany needed a new leader like
Tony Blair, Blair responded, "What Germany needs is a matter of
Germany."
</P>
<P>
In a clear snub at Schroeder, Kohl answered the same question
by saying, "Germany does not have a Tony Blair." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
