<HEADLINE> Greek Equities Hit Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The Greek equities set a record
high on the Athens Stock Exchange Friday with the general index
closing 3.13 percent higher at 1,919.91 points for the first time
in history.
</P>
<P>
The bourse index has risen 24.88 percent since the Greek
national currency drachma joined the European exchange rate
mechanism (ERM) as of Saturday, denoting a 14 percent devaluation
against the European currency unit (ECU).
</P>
<P>
The bourse's 20-blue chip index, the FTSE/ASE-20, also scored a
new high at 1,125.9 points.
</P>
<P>
Trading remained extremely heavy with turnover at 108.7 billion
drachmas (about 332 million U.S. dollars) to total 472 billion
drachmas (about 1.43 billion dollars) for the week, or a daily
average of 94.6 billion drachmas (about 289 million dollars) from
21.2 billion drachmas (about 64.8 million dollars) the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
Advancing shares outpaced declines 184 to 47 with another 21
stocks unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that drachma's devaluation had lessened the
danger of further currency turmoil and led to a gradual decline in
domestic interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
