<HEADLINE> At Least 7 Killed in Apparent Tornado in Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- At least seven people were
killed and 70 others injured in an apparent tornado that tore
through northern Gainesville, Georgia, Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The storm also damaged homes, farm buildings and an elementary
school, and left more than 12,000 people without power, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The Hall County sheriff's department reported that five people,
including two children, were killed when the storms hit their
mobile homes and another was killed in a car. The seventh victim
was a four-year-old girl in neighboring White County.
</P>
<P>
Northeast Georgia Medical Center in Gainesville said it has
treated 57 people with cuts, bruises and abdominal injuries,
</P>
<P>
The storm, which struck the area at about 6:30 a.m. EST,
smashed to pieces waterfront homes on scenic Lake Lanier, cut
trees and damaged several poultry farm buildings containing
hundreds of chickens each.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said there were trees everywhere and roofs across the
road. About a third of Lanier Elementary School was damaged and
two portable buildings were destroyed at North Hall Middle
School. 
</P>
