<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Conveys Annan's Letter to Cypriot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's Special Advisor Diego Cordovez Friday conveyed a letter
from Annan to Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides, hoping the
bicommunal peace talks on the island are to be resumed as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Cordovez after his meeting with Clerides,
during which they discussed the issue of resumption of Cyprus
peace talks which went into deadlock following two rounds of
bicommunal talks last summer.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy told reporters that the U.N. chief and his
Cyprus envoys are bound by the existing Security Council
resolutions in their efforts to settle the protracted Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
"I am trying to find a way to proceed with negotiations,
bridge the differences between the two positions and continue the
search for a peace settlement," the U.N. envoy noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he explained that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash rejected the idea of going to the Security Council to
change the current mandate and President Clerides does not accept
the idea of "state-to-state" talks.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez had a meeting Thursday with Denktash, during which
the Turkish Cypriot leader reiterated his position of no
participation in the peace talks unless his breakaway state
unilaterally declared in 1983 in northern Cyprus is recognized by
the international community.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy stressed that "We have to follow the
resolutions of the Security Council, the Secretary-General has
been given a mandate, we have to follow the mandate and try to
achieve a settlement which is in line with those resolutions of
the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
"Now if one or the other wants to change that, they can try to
change it in the Security Council," he added, noting that "unless
the Security Council changes this, we are bound by the existing
resolutions."
</P>
<P>
So far, negotiations to settle the long-standing Cyprus problem
have been carried out between the leaders of the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot communities in accordance with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and the international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island as a bi-zonal and
bi-communal federal state through peace talks, but so far no
tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez had a meeting Friday afternoon with Denktash in the
Turkish-controlled northern part of Nicosia. It was the second
meeting between the two in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy is expected to have a second meeting with
President Clerides Saturday morning. He will leave for Athens and
Ankara on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
