<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Arrested for Hacking Pentagon Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. officials said a
confederacy of teenage computer hacker groups targeted the
Pentagon and other U.S. sensitive government agencies in a series
of highly sophisticated attacks during the past seven to 10
months.
</P>
<P>
The hackers were based in Israel and the United States. They
apparently did not obtain any classified information, U.S. Justice
Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
Two California teen-agers, one Washington State young person
and three Israeli teens have been arrested in a joint U.S.-Israeli
investigation.
</P>
<P>
The names of the two California suspects were not released, but
the suspect from Carson, Washington, was 20-year-old Calidan Levi
Coffman.
</P>
<P>
NASA Inspector General Roberta Gross called Coffman "one of the
U.S. ringleaders of the Internet hacking group known as `ViRii.'"
</P>
<P>
An 18-year-old Israeli hacker, who calls himself "The
analyzer," was placed under house arrest in Israel Wednesday and
questioned Thursday. The Justice Department in Washington
identified him as Ehud Tenebaum. Two more 18-year-olds in Israel
were also placed under house arest after being identified by the
investigators.
</P>
<P>
All three Israeli teenagers have admitted their involvement in
the computer intrusions, the U.S. Federal Investigation Bureau
(FBI) said.
</P>
<P>
The three Israeli suspects were working with two juveniles in
Cloverdale, California. They hacked their way into U.S. Department
of Defense and other federal agency computers, FBI said. They also
entered Israeli government computers and commercial and
educational systems in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The ViRii investigation was triggered in June when security
officials at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena,
California, discovered one of their Internet computer servers was
actually being controlled by an outside source.
</P>
<P>
NASA's Computer Crimes Division and other government agencies
including the Naval Intelligence Service, the Air Force Office of
Special Investigations and the FBI eventually uncovered a link
between what they say was Coffman's group and a mysterious Israeli
hacker known as "The Analyzer" who headed a shadowy group called
the "Israeli Internet Underground."
</P>
<P>
The investigation picked up steam in February when the
Pentagon's computers came under a massive attack characterized by
Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre as the "most sophisticated" in
its history.
</P>
<P>
Investigators are still looking for another hacker, thought to
be a Massachusetts teen who goes under the code name "FAC."
</P>
<P>
Investigators said it was not clear at this point what their
motives were. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
