<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Rightwing Hijacks Regional Election by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- France's central-right Union for
French Democracy (UDF) Friday hijacked the regional elections
outcome by allying with the far-right National Front (FN), seizing
several left-dominated regional councils and winning 11 councils
out of 22.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist-led leftwing coalition, which came out the winner
in the elections Sunday, only won three councils in France proper
and the one in the overseas territory of Frency Guyana so far,
while the Gaullist Rally for the Republic (RPR) won two councils.
</P>
<P>
The UDF and RPR deputies also delayed the voting in four other
regions, including the Paris region and the Provence-Alpes-Cote
d'Azur, where the left won a narrow victory but the number of
elected deputies is considerable.
</P>
<P>
If the UDF and RPR deputies continue to ally with the FN in
these regions, the political map of France will remain
right-dominated as six years ago, when the previous regional
elections were held.
</P>
<P>
Only in the western region of Franche-Comte, Jean-Francois
Humbert, a UDF candidate, resigned after being elected president
of the regional council with the support from FN.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist and Communist leaders immediately condemned the
allying between UDF deputies with the FN, while RPR President
Philippe Seguin denounced those who allied with the far-right.
</P>
<P>
Socialist Party First Secretary Francois Hollande said the day
would "remain a sinister day in the history of the republic,"
while Communist Party National Secretary Robert Hue described what
happened as "a denial of democracy."
</P>
<P>
The FN hailed the alliance with the UDF as a victory. The FN
European Parliament deputy and head of the party's campaign in
Paris, Jean-Yves Le Gallou, said that "the containment against the
FN has now cracked." 
</P>
</TEXT>
