<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zambia-Angola Relations Strained over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- A six-member Angolan delegation
is in Zambia to verify the alleged arms supply from Zambia to
Angola's rebellious National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba said here on Thursday that
the delegation is free to go ahead and find out the truth to have
a better impression on Zambian side of the common border.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that Angola remains a friendly and sister country
to Zambia despite misconception and mistakes that could have been
made by nationalists of either country.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said it is important for the two countries to meet and
resolve the allegations because the issues at hand are important
and threaten the security of both countries.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan military and government officials, who arrived in
Zambia on Tuesday, have held meetings with their Zambian
counterparts in Mongu in western province bordering Angola.
</P>
<P>
The officials from both sides started to carry out spot
inspections on the Zambian side of the border.
</P>
<P>
Angolan ambassador Manuel Augusto charged on March 5 that
Zambians were supplying arms to UNITA through Zambia border.
</P>
<P>
He said "we do not believe that the Zambian government can
support UNITA in any way. But we are saying some individuals
including Zambian citizens are using the Zambian territory to
support UNITA."
</P>
<P>
He warned that while his country does not wish to have a
repeat of the Congo-Brazzaville and Congo Kinshasa incidents
where the Angolan government participated in dislodging the
governments there. "Angola does not rule out any option if UNITA
does not stop getting arms from some territories."
</P>
<P>
He said that Angola had tried to negotiate with former Zaire
and the Congo-Brazzaville governments, but things never worked,
only resulting in Angola's invading the two nations and
dislodging the sitting governments, which supported UNITA.
</P>
<P>
One of the companies that supply arms to UNITA is a
Zambian-based South African firm, said the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Zambian government must enforce control on
its side of the border so that UNITA does not take advantage of
the border to acquire firearms.
</P>
<P>
He described the situation in Zambian-Angolan border as
serious, saying that the border is almost under the control of
UNITA.
</P>
<P>
But Zambian President Frederick Chiluba denied on March 12
that his government has any involvement in supplying arms to any
country.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we are a very peaceful and friendly nation and
we have no capacity to give arms to UNITA."
</P>
<P>
However, the president said that his government will
investigate allegations that Zambia is being used as a transit
point for arms to UNITA, which fought a civil war of about 20
years against the Angolan government after the country's
independence in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba also dismissed as false claims that UNITA soldiers
have replaced refugees at Maheba refugee camp in Solwezi in
Zambia's northern province.
</P>
<P>
He said that his foreign minister Keli Walubita will go to
Angola soon to brief Angolan side on the measures his government
has taken.
</P>
<P>
On March 15 Walubita said the alleged arms supply to UNITA
through Zambia has already been referred to the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
