willingness to sign a non-aggression pact with neighboring Turkey
as part of its efforts to improve the strained relations between
the two countries for decades.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that the Greek government was very favorable
towards the signing of a non-aggression pact with Turkey as long
as this accord would not be contrary to international law and
international treaties governing the status quo in the region.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a statement recently made by Turkish
Defense Minister Ismet Sezgin in which Sezgin did not rule out the
possibility of signing such a pact with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Reppas said that Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos Thursday handed over a letter to the Turkish ambassador
in Athens in which Athens reiterated its standing position on the
proposals, in essence a rejection of Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem's five-point plan for dialogue on all differences
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Greece criticized Cem's plan as "a simple restatement of issues
already being dealt with and of the standing Turkish stance for
dialogue on all issues." 
