<HEADLINE> German Police Clash with Anti-Nuclear Demonstrators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 20 (Xinhua) -- German riot police on Friday turned
water cannons on hundreds of anti-nuclear activists who staged a
sit-in protest on railway lines near the northern German town of
Ahaus to try to block a controversial shipment of nuclear waste to
a nearby nuclear depot.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the arrival of a special train carrying six
containers of spent fuel rods from two nuclear power plants in
southern Germany, several sections of the rail lines had to be
repaired because of damages made by demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
Police also had to cut free several demonstrators who chained
themselves onto the track.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,000 anti-nuclear protesters gathered in Ahaus earlier
Friday and tried to force their way into the railway station which
was sealed by the police. Several people were wounded during the
clashes.
</P>
<P>
At about 20:40 local time, the nuclear waste train finally
arrived at its destination through a 3.7-kilometer-long private
track leading from Ahaus to the nuclear storage.
</P>
<P>
The transport, which started Thursday from the southern German
state of Baden-Wuerttemberg, has required a total of 30,000
policemen to provide protection. About 400 anti-nuclear activists
have been taken into custody temporarily in the two days. 
</P>
