<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea, Japan Agree to Resume Fishery Talks Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 21 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan Saturday
agreed to resume suspended talks next month on the revision of a
1965 fishery pact that Japan terminated on January 23 this year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached by South Korean Foreign Minister Park
Chung-soo and his Japanese counterpart Keizo Obuchi during their
meeting here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, who arrived in Seoul on Saturday for a three-day visit
and met South Korean President Kim Dae-jung earlier, proposed
resuming the talks.
</P>
<P>
"I feel regret over the situation," Obuchi said. "The Japanese
government could not help but inform the Korean government of its
termination of the accord because of protests from private fishery
agencies and politicians in Japan."
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Park urged Japan to take a sincere and positive
attitude toward the restoration of the fishery talks.
</P>
<P>
"If Japan's capture of Korean fishing boats re-occurs, future
negotiations will not go smoothly. Accordingly, Japan's sincere
efforts are required," Park noted.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to open a Seoul-Tokyo security policy
meeting as soon as possible. The meeting, originally scheduled to open
in January this year, was delayed due to Japan's unilateral
termination of the fishery agreement.
</P>
<P>
Revising the 1965 fishery agreement has ailed the two nations
for a long time since they must redraw their sea boundaries under
a new United Nations maritime convention.
</P>
<P>
On January 23, Japan announced its unilateral repeal of the
fishery accord after South Korea refused to accepted its demands
in the past two years' 10 rounds of negotiations for revising the
accord.
</P>
<P>
A day later, South Korea passed a resolution urging the
government to take all possible measures to guarantee Korean
fishermen's interests, including scrapping self-regulation on the
operation of South Korean fishing boats near Japan's waters.
</P>
</TEXT>
