<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Observes World Water Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe Saturday joined the rest
of world in commemorating World Water Day set for Sunday whose
theme this year focuses on the sustainable use of ground water.
</P>
<P>
Cain Mathema, deputy minister of rural resources and water
development, said in a statement that the use of ground water is
on the increase in Zimbabwe and should be monitored to minimize
its depletion and pollution because it plays an important role in
times of drought.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his ministry has just completed consultations on
important pieces of legislation which will guide the development
and management of national water resources into the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
The draft Zimbabwe National Water Bill will soon be tabled
before parliament and if approved will sensitize the management
of ground water in the same manner as surface water, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The new bill proposes to invoke stiffer penalties against
pollution of water through the application of the polluter pays
principle," Mathema said.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy minister, the government continues to
place emphasis and accords a high priority to water development
countrywide as witnessed by the increased construction of dams to
give the nation adequate water.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the World Water Day is to promote public
awareness on water-related issues which include conservation and
sustainable utilization of water resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environmental Protection Industry Gaining Momentum (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The output of China's
environmental protection industry has registered an annual average
increase of 20 percent in the 1990s, with yearly output hitting 40
billion yuan (five billion U.S. dollars), according to the
Association of China Environmental Protection Industry (ACEPI).
</P>
<P>
"The new industry boasts a certain amount of economic strength
and scale," said Yu Yuefeng, vice director of ACEPI, adding that
the Chinese government has attached great importance to
environmental protection and has taken a series of measures to
step up pollution treatment, which has provided opportunities for
the industry's further development.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Chinese companies have taken environmental
protection or comprehensive utilization of resources into
consideration for production.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, China's accumulated investment in environmental
protection will reach 400 billion yuan, of which the investment in
the first-phase landscaping project from 1996-2000 will hit 188.8
billion yuan, an official with the State Environmental Protection
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The big environmental protection projects China is carrying out
include water pollution treatment of Huaihe, Liaohe, Haihe, Caohu,
Taihu and Dianchi, as well as treatment of acid rain and sulfur
dioxide air pollution across many provinces, cities, and regions.
</P>
<P>
The environmental protection industry can provide technology
and equipment for large-scale pollution treatment, comprehensive
utilization of resources, and spreading clean production, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign enterprises such as those in the United States,
Germany, and Japan are also trying to gain an edge in the
potentially big Chinese market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environmental Protection Industry Gaining Momentum (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Some of these products have reached world advanced level," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Chinese production of equipment dealing with air pollution
treatment will develop rapidly in the next five years, he said,
adding that the newly developed Chinese product of water pollution
prevention and treatment equipment should gain an important market
share.
</P>
<P>
Other Chinese competitive products mentioned by Li include
comprehensive utilization facilities treating solid waste whose
output is predicted to surpass that of water and air pollution
treatment equipment, and garbage-burning facilities with a daily
capacity of 150 to 1,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
"It is not impossible for China's environmental protection
industry to boast the exporting capabilities amounting to hundreds
of millions U.S. dollars after 3-to-5 years of development," said
Li Siyu.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese provinces of Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Liaoning, Tianjin
and Guangdong, and the city of Shanghai have taken the lead in
developing the environmental protection industry, and they are
expected to implement a series of new programs to uphold their
advantages.
</P>
<P>
With an annual increase rate of 25 percent, the environmental
protection industry of Jiangsu Province should reach an output of
20 billion yuan (2.5 billion U.S. dollars) in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has assigned Liaoning Province in
northeast China as the production base for the nation's
environmental protection industry, and the municipal city of
Tianjin also set forth a goal of establishing itself as a
production center for north China.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, will
make intensive efforts to develop new technologies, techniques and
products through establishing an environmental protection
industrial park zone.
</P>
<P>
"The newly booming Chinese industry of environmental protection
will also actively seek Sino-foreign economic and technological
cooperation to promote the development of the industry," said Li
Yuefeng. 
</P>
</TEXT>
