<HEADLINE> Canadian Envoy Calls for Increased Trade with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian High Commissioner to
Zimbabwe Anne Charles Saturday predicted that there is potential
for trade increase between Zimbabwe and Canada through joint
ventures.
</P>
<P>
Charles told the Zimbabwe News Agency that owing to Canada's
open market policy, there are no restrictions for goods imported
or exported to Canada.
</P>
<P>
She said more still needed to be done in the field of
technology transfer and Zimbabwe could benefit from Canadian
technology.
</P>
<P>
"We encourage more business to be done by the two countries
and the interest of business opportunities we have received from
both countries is fantastic," said the envoy.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Zimbabwe was among the top group of countries which
conducted business with Canada with exports of different goods in
excess of 16.6 million Canadian Dollars (11.6 million U.S.
Dollars), she said.
</P>
<P>
Canada imported tobacco, cotton and precious metals from
Zimbabwe while Zimbabwe imported machinery.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian High Commission in Zimbabwe was currently in the
process of establishing a web site on the internet, she said,
adding that the focus of the site will be to promote and increase
the accessibility of information to Canadian companies by
Zimbabwe's business sectors and other southern African countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
