<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Arabs to Protest Land Confiscation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Arabs decided Saturday
to stage widespread demonstrations on March 30 to mark the Land
Day and protest Israel's continued confiscation of their land and
property.
</P>
<P>
The annual event was to remember six Israeli Arabs, three from
the northern Arab town of Sakhnin, who were killed by Israeli
soldiers in a demonstration in 1976 to protest Israel's usurp of
Arab land in Galilee in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
This year's decision to hold the Land Day protests was made by
the Supreme Council of Israeli Arabs that include Arab lawmakers
and heads of local Arab councils who met in the northern city
Shefaram.
</P>
<P>
The council said that three major demonstrations would be held
across the country, including Sakhnin, western Galilee and Negev
in the south.
</P>
<P>
It said the demonstrations are to protest against continued
confiscation of land and properties of Arabs, whose population is
estimated at about 1 million.
</P>
<P>
The past annual Land Day protests usually passed relatively
quietly, but Israeli security forces are expected to keep high
alert this year against possible outbreak of violence at a time
when the peace process is deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Arabs, who complain about racial discrimination in the
dominantly Jewish state, closely identify themselves with the
Palestinians in the territories and support their struggle for
independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
