<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Four-Party Talks on Korean Peninsula Wind Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The six-day second plenary session
of the four-party talks to seek a lasting and stable peace on the
Korean Peninsula ended here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jian, China's assistant foreign minister and chairman of
the current round of the talks, said in a chairman's statement
that China, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, South Korea
and the United States of America had an "in-depth exchange of
views on substantive issues relating to permanent peace on the
Korean peninsula."
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere during the talks from March 16-21 was "candid,
serious and calm." Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"We were not, however, able to narrow the differences
sufficiently to move forward in our work at this time," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Major achievements of the second plenary included:
</P>
<P>
-- This was the first meeting in which the four-party talks
moved into a substantive stage.
</P>
<P>
-- The four parties clarified some of the important differences.
</P>
<P>
-- The four parties agreed that it is necessary to set up
sub-committees.
</P>
<P>
"The four-party talks are inherently a long and difficult
process," said the chairman's statement. "The fact that we are
here together today demonstrates the commitment of all the parties
to our common search for a permanent peace."
</P>
<P>
The specific date of the third plenary session to be chaired by
South Korea has not yet been decided, but it is expected to occur
in about three months in Geneva according to the arrangement of
the first plenary session last December.
</P>
<P>
The four delegations expressed their thanks to the Swiss
government for its assistance in serving as host to the current
session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Expatriate Civil Servant Sees Posthandover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Nine months after Hong Kong
became a Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China, work and
life have been as usual for Richard A. Siegel, who led 800 staff
members in the Civil Aviation Department through the transition.
</P>
<P>
When asked if anything has changed after the handover, the
Director of Civil Aviation told Xinhua: "There has been no
change. The short answer is no."
</P>
<P>
"(In the civil service), the structures and the people remain
in place, and all assurances that were stated before the handover
have been honored," said the high-ranking expatriate civil servant
of the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
His department continues to look after Hong Kong International
Airport, Kai Tak, which is among the busiest, safest and most
efficient airports in the world.
</P>
<P>
"We're a technical department, and we deal with technical
issues and maintain the high standard," said the 54-year-old
Briton, who has been with the Department since he came to Hong
Kong in 1973. No wonder he has a high personal regard for the
department, saying: " We're a good team and we work well
together."
</P>
<P>
Siegel also took a lot of pride of his former staff members,
who now become the backbone at the Airport Authority, a body
taking care of the building and management of the New Airport at
Chek Lap Kok, scheduled for operation in July this year.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy to see them taking the Kai Tak tradition to the New
Airport, and taking the Hong Kong experience to the New Airport,"
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Expatriate Civil Servant Sees Posthandover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
His diary remains pretty full -- chairing the director meetings
every two weeks, joining in discussion on the management of Chek
Lap Kok new airport, planning the transfer of operations from Kai
Tak to Chek Lap Kok, and many more. Usually he works 12 hours a
day from eight to eight, but still manages to find time listening
to classical music and reading biography.
</P>
<P>
However, in Siegel's eyes, something has become different after
the handover. In October 1997, he attended a regional conference
of Director General of Civil Aviation, where for the first time he
sat under the Bauhinia flag, the regional flag of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
In November 1997, He took part in the Conference on
Airworthiness of the International Civil Aviation Organization
(ICAO) in Montreal, for the first time as a member of the Chinese
delegation. Hong Kong used to join the British delegation on the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
"I was given a very warm welcome by the Chinese delegation to
the ICAO," he said, "They were very helpful and friendly, and give
me great assistance."
</P>
<P>
"Under the British delegation, I sat right at the back of the
hall; under the Chinese delegation, I sat right in the front of
the hall," said the Hong Kong official, "you see, they (Chinese)
change my position in the hall."
</P>
<P>
Besides the arrangement of sitting, he was impressed by another
aspect. "We're given more latitude under China this time than we
worked under the British," he explained, "we have established a
clear mechanism for communications with the Chinese in the
mainland, and the mechanism works well."
</P>
<P>
Sitting in his 46th-floor office where commands a good view of
the-glass-glazed skyscrapers in Central, Siegel said: "When I
look outside this window, I see what is stated in the Basic Law
and in the Joint Declaration is what has happened."
</P>
<P>
"'Hong Kong people ruling Hong Kong' and 'a high degree of
autonomy' work very well. The concept of 'one country, two
systems' has gone onto a good start. If it continues, the
prosperity of Hong Kong will be ensured," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
His confidence in the future of Hong Kong was built upon his
25-year connection with this Chinese city. When he arrived in
early 1970's, he did not intend to stay this long in Hong Kong,
but after he had been for a while, he fell in love with the Kai
Tak Airport, the people and the city.
</P>
<P>
Kai Tak is where he began his career and life in Hong
Kong. Starting from the passenger terminal, he later took the
position of the Airport General Manager for ten years through the
80s, in his words, a very challenging time of rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, Kai Tak will be closed with the opening of
the New Airport at Chek Lap Kok. Siegel said: "I have mixed
feelings. Kai Tak is like your grandma. It is a wonderful good
lady. It serves so long, so well."
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that Hong Kong needs a new airport with more
capacity, and Chek Lap Kok is the future of aviation in Hong
Kong. "I'll be sad to see it (Kai Tak) go, and I'll be glad to
turn the light down," said the man, who called himself an
aviation man.
</P>
<P>
"I have always been proud to have been part of the city, even
in the future wherever I go and wherever I am," said Siegel, who
is expected to retire in six years.
</P>
<P>
He decided to stay in 1970's because he was motivated by a
"can do" spirit in Hong Kong. The city is so unique that "if it
can be done anywhere in the world, it can be done here", and the
people are vibrant, positive and hard working.
</P>
<P>
During the Sino-British negotiations in the 1980's, again, he
decided to stay on to transition. "Because I believe in the future
of Hong Kong and I have faith in the people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
