<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman's exports volume in 1997 rose to 2.934 billion
riyals (7.6 billion U.S. dollars), the Omani Economy Ministry
said. Oman's imports during the same year rose by 9.8 percent to
1.933 billion riyals (about 5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) will levy
progressive additional taxes on tobacco and its derivatives in
compliance with relevant collective moves made by the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law promulgated by UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin
Sultan Al-Nahyan, the tax levied on imported tobacco and its
derivatives should be raised gradually. This rise, which is due
to start on July 1, 1998, will bring the tax to 80 percent. This
tax will further to 90 percent on July 1, 1999, and to 100 percent
in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The new Moroccan government announced Friday that the
customs duties on grain imports would be raised. It is the first
measures of its kind taken by the government since it was
appointed by King Hassan II a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Government Spokesman Khaled Elaiwa said that Prime Minister
Abderrahmane El-Youssoufi signed Friday a decree to raise the
customs duties on wheat imports to enable small farmers market their
products at good prices.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Bahrain's Civil Service System is now considering
forbidding government officials from carrying and using the mobile
telephone while working, United Arab Emirates newspaper
"Al-Ittihad" reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This comes at the request of a ministry that has complained
about using the mobile telephone of its employees in personal
contacts, which affects the efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The Bahraini Ministry of Education last year issued a decree
prohibiting the use of mobile telephone in schools. The Bahraini
government had also forbidden motorists to use mobile telephone
while driving with the aim of decreasing traffic accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
