<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Seek U.S. Backing to Pullout From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai is to visit the United States next week to seek
Washington's backing to Israel's initiative on a conditional
withdrawal from south Lebanon, Israel Radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai will hold talks with senior U.S. officials to
discuss the Israeli readiness to withdraw from south Lebanon so as
to seek U.S. support, which is crucial to the success of the
initiative.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai's U.S. trip was decided after Israeli security
Cabinet voiced support to his proposal for a unilateral pullout
from south Lebanon in keeping with the United Nations Security
Council Resolution 425, which called for unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But his proposal conditioned Israeli withdrawal on the
Lebanese government's agreement to deploy troops in the region to
ensure safety of Israel's northern border.
</P>
<P>
To pull out from south Lebanon, where Israel is bogged down in
a tough guerrilla war with anti-Israeli Hezbollah (Party of God)
fighters.
</P>
<P>
An average 35 Israeli soldiers are killed annually in south
Lebanon since Israel's establishment of a 1,200 square-kilometer
security zone in south Lebanon with the aim to protect Israel's
northern area from cross-border guerilla attacks in 1985.
</P>
<P>
In the latest casualties, six Israeli soldiers were slightly
injured late Friday when Hezbollah gunmen shelled Israeli outposts.
</P>
<P>
Analyzers believed that the chances of Israeli initiative on
Lebanese withdrawal depend on whether Lebanese government agrees
to deploy troops in south Lebanon in the event of an Israeli
pullout and whether Syria permits Lebanon to do so.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Syria will not agree to let Israel off the
hook by withdrawing from south Lebanon while continuing
occupation of the strategic Golan Heights which Israel seized
from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Although Lebanon and Syria have welcomed Israel's initiative
to withdraw unilaterally from south Lebanon, they demanded such
pullout be unconditional only.
</P>
<P>
Due to the Lebanese and Syrian attitudes, Israeli officials
intimated that any breakthrough on the initiative would come
about primarily through direct U.S. involvement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
