<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,000 People Join Firefighting in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- At least 1,000 people gathered in
Samarinda, capital of Indonesia's East Kalimantan province,
Saturday to join a two-week program to put out forest fires raging
in the 40,000 hectares of the Kutai National Park, Antara News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The program is being funded by the National Development
Planning Board, the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and
the Integrated Forest Fire Management.
</P>
<P>
Antara gave no details of the program.
</P>
<P>
Kutai National Park Head Warsito said the fires had ravaged
more than 44,789 hectares of virgin forests, with losses estimated
at 1.85 billion rupiah (one U.S. dollar equals 9,500 rupiah).
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, up to 1,000 fires were raging
in East Kalimantan Friday and the situation is set to dramatically
deteriorate as the prolonged drought drags on.
</P>
<P>
A government forest official in Samarinda said the situation is
becoming "hopeless."
</P>
<P>
The fires had been deliberately lit by farmers and plantation
and timber firms to clear ground, he said. "The government is
doing its best but these farmers and the companies still start
fires."
</P>
<P>
Some officials estimated the fires, which have ravaged more
than 80,000 hectares of brush and forest in East Kalimantan over
the last two months, have incurred losses amounting to 76.2
billion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
Fires in the islands of Kalimantan and Sumatra last year sent a
haze across a large part of Southeast Asia, causing widespread
health problems and massive transport disruptions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
