<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyacinth Furniture Planned in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is planning to produce
furniture from hyacinth, the water weed which turns disastrous in
Lake Victoria, The New Vision reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
David Nsalasata, superintendent of Lusira Prison in eastern
Kampala, is seeking assistance for commercial development of the
weed.
</P>
<P>
There are various designs for commercial development of
hyacinth. But the prison officer told a parliament team visiting
the prison earlier this week that his prison has the potential of
producing high-quality furniture on a large scale from the weed.
</P>
<P>
The problem is lack of equipment to harvest and transport the
weed from nearby Murchison Bay of Lake Victoria, the world's
second largest fresh water lake.
</P>
<P>
There are ready market, Nsalasata claimed, adding what they
need is adequate supply of the weed.
</P>
<P>
There is a Japanese weed harvester at nearby Port Bell, but
the chopped weeds are not suitable for making furniture, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The prison has two digesters and a storage trunk that produced
enough biogas for the prison. The biogas is produced from a
mixture of water hyacinth with cow dung. But the facilities are
not enough for commercial production, the prison officer said.
</P>
<P>
Water hyacinth invaded Nile waters including Lake Victoria in
1950s and developed into an environmental disaster in recent
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
