<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Eradicate Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is making a
new law outlawing child labor, a senior official of the
Department of Labor said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation will be so stringent that even parents who
urge their children under the age of 15 to take weekend or
holiday jobs could fall foul of the law.
</P>
<P>
Anyone found guilty of employing child labor will be
prosecuted, said Fatima Bhyat, acting director of Minimum
Standards Section of the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that there were about 200,000 children aged
between 10 and 14 who are working for a wage. Most are working on
farms but cases have been reported of children working in
sweatshops.
</P>
<P>
Child labor is reportedly exploited in many ways from children
begging for money in the street for their parents, to children
working on farms, children involved in pornography and
prostitution, children used by organized gangs and children
selling fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
To curb child labor, the Department of Labor is promulgating
the Basic Conditions of Employment of Act in two phases, with the
section on child labor being implemented on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This sets 15 as the minimum age for employment and protects
children of 15 up to 18 from hazardous employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
