<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Accuses Cameroun of Fresh Attack in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has charged that Cameroun
seriously injured at least 43 of its citizens in a fresh attack
in the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula, as the dispute between the two
countries over it is being handled by the World Court.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Headquarters said here Friday that Cameroun, using
a helicopter mounted with a machine-gun, strafed troops and
civilians in several areas of Bakassi, where both countries have
claimed ownership.
</P>
<P>
In the aerial attack, five Nigerian soldiers, 20 market women
and more than 18 school children were wounded, according to
Defense Spokesmen Col. Godwin Ugbo.
</P>
<P>
The attack, which took place Thursday morning, was aimed at
drawing Nigeria into a retaliatory attack, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ugbo, the Cameroun armed forces gendarmes have
within the past one year attacked innocent fishermen in the area,
killing some and abducting many.
</P>
<P>
"They have equally provoked our troops, but we have restrained
ourselves not be to drawn into any form of hostilities" in
respect of the ruling by the International Court of Justice on
the cease-fire agreement between the two countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Some two weeks ago, Nigeria alarmed that Cameroun had moved
about 5,000 of its troops to the borderline in Bakassi, alleging
that Cameroun had been acquiring more military hardware since it
declared dispute with Nigeria over the ownership of oil-rich area
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to defense sources, Cameroun has a total military
strength of 26,000 made up of 11,500 soldiers, 1,500 naval
officers and ratings, 1,000 air force officers and men and 12,000
gendarmes.
</P>
<P>
It has, apart from three reconnaissance early warning radar,
acquired at least 24 planes and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Several European nationals were also accused of being involved
in the preparation for an attack in Nigeria's position in
Bakassi.
</P>
<P>
"The federal military government of Nigeria views the heavy
concentration of troops by the Camerounian government at the
border as an affront, and appeals for restraint," Ugbo said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun have been clashing since early 1994 on
Bakassi, a territory of about 1,000 square kilometers and
believed to be rich in oil resources.
</P>
<P>
The case was filed to the International Court of Justice by
Cameroun in 1994 and is currently being heard at the Hague, the
Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0110 </DOCNO>
