<HEADLINE> Corser Claims Superbike Pole Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Australian Troy Corser marked a
dream return to the Superbike World Championship Saturday when he
claimed pole position for the opening round at Phillip Island in
Australia's Victoria state on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Despite an injured left ankle, Corser recorded a time of
1 minute 34.971 seconds in Saturday's controversial Superpole
shoot-out to move from fifth on the grid to first, although the
26-year-old had reservations about the new qualifying format.
</P>
<P>
"I don't agree with Superpole," said Corser, the 1996 world
superbike champion.
</P>
<P>
"I'm here to race, not do one lap. I've got a good race
set-up, and that's what's important for tomorrow, not being
fastest after just one lap."
</P>
<P>
Corser is receiving treatment for injuries he suffered in a 240
kmh accident during testing at the circuit last Wednesday, and
admitted he was not 100 percent fit.
</P>
<P>
Corser edged out the Castrol Honda of New Zealander Aaron
Slight for pole by only 0.026 seconds, with Ducati factory riders
Pier Francesco Chili and Carl Fogarty only 0.078 seconds and 0.011
seconds slower respectively.
</P>
<P>
The casualty of Superpole was Australian Suzuki rider Peter
Goddard, who had earlier qualified fastest in the 36-bike field,
but dropped to seventh-fastest after the one lap Superpole
final qualifying session.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to spend tonight in my own bed rather than one in a
hospital, so I opted for safety," said 33-year-old Goddard, the
reigning World Endurance champion.
</P>
<P>
The first of Sunday's two 22-lap Superbike races will start at
midway with heat two scheduled for 15:30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
