<HEADLINE> Briefing Session for Subsector Elections Candidates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 21 (Xinhua) -- A briefing session for
candidates of the Election Committee (EC) subsector elections was
held at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center here
Saturday Morning.
</P>
<P>
During the session, Justice K.H. Woo, chairman of the Electoral
Affairs Commission, briefed the candidates on some important
regulations and guidelines related to the EC subsector elections
to be held in Hong Kong on April 2 as well as specific matters
concerning the polling day arrangement.
</P>
<P>
The session was aimed at ensuring the subsector elections to be
conducted in a fair, open and honest manner, Woo said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the session, candidates drew lots to determine
the order of names on ballot paper and to allocate designated
spots for display of election advertisements.
</P>
<P>
Optical Mark Reader for counting was also demonstrated during
the session.
</P>
<P>
The nomination for the EC subsector elections finished Friday
with a total of 1,107 nominations received.
</P>
<P>
Of the 800 seats which make up the Election committee, 77 will
be filled by ex-officio members comprising Hong Kong deputies to
the National People's Congress and members of the Provisional
Legislative council, 40 seats will be filled by nominees from the
religious subsector and 683 seats will be returned by election in
the remaining subsectors.
</P>
<P>
Due to the number of the candidates from the four subsectors of
commerce, industry, the Hong Kong Chinese Enterprises Association
and the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference
equivalent to that of the allocated seats, so the nominated 95
members from these subsectors will be automatically members of the
Election Committee without election.
</P>
<P>
That means 588 seats will be returned by elections in the
remaining 31 subsectors on April 2.
</P>
<P>
The first Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region shall be composed of 60 members, with 20
returned by geographical constituencies through direct elections,
10 by the Election Committee and 30 by functional constituencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
