<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Calls for Economic Thrift in New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei has called on the Iranian people and the government
to practice "reasonable thrift" and fight against "extravagant
consumption" in the new Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to advise the dear Iranian nation against extravagant
consumption and everybody must think seriously of thrift and
economical consumption," Khamenei said in his new year address to
the Iranian nation on Friday night. The new Iranian year started
on Saturday on Iranian calendar.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA quoted him as saying that "there
is no justification for us to indulge in extravagance at the
cost of sacrificing the greater future of our nation or our
long-term goals or even our important present-day preferences and
we have no right to overlook our future needs."
</P>
<P>
"My primary recommendation to the people this year is to be
wise and consume economically," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian ailing economy was worsened by an decrease of oil
incomes as a result of oil price drop in world market during the
past Iranian year, since oil incomes make up 80-90 percent of the
country's foreign exchanges revenues.
</P>
<P>
The country's oil revenue during the 11 months of the past
Iranian year stood at 14.3 billion U.S. dollars with an average
price at 15.7 dollars per barrel. It is difficult to achieve 17.7
billion dollars oil revenue in the government's budget for the
year.
</P>
<P>
Mainly because of the reduction of oil revenue, the budget
deficit in the last Iranian year reached 4.57 billion dollars and
it will rise to 11.4 billion dollars in the current Iranian year,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of Iranian rial for U.S. dollar also soared
up to 5,250 in the black market on the eve of the Iranian new year
from 4,800 at the beginning of 1998, although the government still
keeps the official rate at 1,750 rials and the export rate at
3,000 rials.
</P>
<P>
Economists and oil experts have warned of a serious economic
crisis in Iran during the new year, because they believed that
Iran's oil earning would be reduced by some 3-4 billion dollars
since the price of Iranian crude has declined to around 11
dollars per barrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Investments Abroad Hit by Economic Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's investments
overseas have been hard hit by the current economic turmoil,
Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The economic woes forced Malaysian businessmen to defer or pull
out of their overseas investment projects, he said in Sungai
Petani, some 400 kilometers north from here.
</P>
<P>
He said they had been hard hit by the credit squeeze in the
region and other difficulties in obtaining capital.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless we are advising them not to default on
memorandums of understanding which they have signed," he was
quoted by the Malaysian national news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the Foreign Ministry had compiled a report on the
effects of the economic crisis on Malaysian entrepreneurs
investing overseas, which he said would be submitted to Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad. But he declined to disclose its
conclusions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
