<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- March 20 was a black day for the French rightwing when the
taboo from the Resistance in World War II and Gaullism was
broken. In five regions where the leftwing has won a relative
majority in regional council elections, the personalities of the
right ignored the instruction from the leaders of Rally for the
Republic and Union for French Democracy and reached a deal with
the far-right National Front for keeping their presidency in the
councils.
</P>
<P>
-- An Argentine commission has revealed some documents which
showed that Cardinal Eugene Tisserant, a French Roman Catholic
prelate who served as leader of the mission of Vatican in eastern
Europe and later nominated as candidate for the pope, wrote to the
Argentine embassy in Rome in 1946 asking Argentina to provide
asylum for some French Nazi collaborators fleeing the country.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The far-right National Front allowed the election of
rightwing personalities to the presidency of five regional
councils on Friday, including former Defense Minister Charles
Millon who was elected as president of the council of the major
industrial region of Rhone-Alpes. This led to a split within the
rightwing, and the RPR president Philippe Seguin described it as
"a terrible convulsion" for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
-- Pope John Paul is to begin Saturday a three-day visit to
Nigeria, during which he will plead for human rights for the
people living under military dictatorship. 
</P>
