<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1000 GMT March 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB -- Croatian President Franjo Tudjman put forward again
his proposal on demilitarization of Bosnia when meeting Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the proposal, Tudjman noted that Bosnia's demilitarization
should be enforced under the guarantees of the international
community and through the signing of agreements with neighboring
Croatia and Yugoslavia safeguarding Bosnia's territorial integrity
and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman told Primakov it is very important to protect Bosnian
Croats who account for only 17.3 percent of the total population,
far less than Bosnian Serbs or Muslims. (Croatia-Russian FM-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Cuban State Council President Fidel Castro said here
Friday that the U.S. lifting of ban on direct flights between the
two countries is "positive and constructive."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with CNN, Castro said that the measure will be
"helpful to a better climate for Cuban-U.S. relations." But he
added he needs to see the full details of the measure.
</P>
<P>
News from Washington reported that President Bill Clinton was
to announce Friday the lifting of ban on direct flights, the
permission of money remittances to relatives in Cuba by Cubans
living in U.S. and the easing of restrictions on U.S. medicine
sales to Cuba. (Cuba-US-Sanctions Easing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A senior United States official said here Friday
that the U.S.-China agreement on nuclear cooperation has paved the
way for American companies to compete against their counterparts
in the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Sandra Kristoff, special assistant to the president and senior
director for Asian programs at the National Security Council, told
reporters that the accord, signed in 1985, came into effect after
Congress failed to respond to President Bill Clinton's
certification before the deadline of March 18. (US-China-Accord)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Chairman of the Russian Communist Party Gennady
Zyuganov said on Friday that Russian foreign policy should put
particular emphasis on developing contacts with countries in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov told a press conference that as a priority, Russia
should develop contacts with countries such as China, India and
Japan, Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The party chief expressed his strong belief that in the coming
21st century, the Asia-Pacific region would play a leading role in
global development. (Russia-Foreign Policy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ZAGREB -- Croatian Presidency of the Republic of Bosnia
Kresimir Zubak said Friday he supported establishing Bosnia as a
non-militarization zone, as proposed by Croatian President Franjo
Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
Zubak made the remarks in Sarajevo, capital of Bosnia during
talks with Mr A. Vershbowon, the United States ambassador to the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In a communique released by his office in Sarajevo, Zubak said
that judged from an economic point of view, the proposal deserved
much attention. (Bosnia-Non-Militarization) 
</P>
</TEXT>
