<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Rejection to Berlin Court Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 21 (Xinhua) - Iran Saturday once again
rejected the Berlin court rule that accused Iranian leaders of
sponsoring state terrorism against Iranian Kurdish rebel leaders
in Germany, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said
Saturday morning that "these claims are unacceptable and lack
legal value and validity."
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the biased statements of the Berlin local
court judge was made in line with a political and propaganda
show which continued for several years," Mohammadi.
</P>
<P>
Last April, the Berlin local court ruled that Iranian
leaders were behind the terrorist killing of four Iranian
Kurdish opposition leaders in the Mykonos restaurant in Berlin
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In a protest to Iran, the European Union (EU) countries
immediately withdrew their ambassadors to Tehran, who returned
last November after the two sides reached a compromise.
</P>
<P>
After 11-month investigation, the Berlin local court judge
repeated the accusation against Iran in his recent statements.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that the Berlin court judge's statements have
been made "on the basis of unfounded allegations of witnesses,
some of whom are implicated in terrorist acts and others are
prosecuted by the Iranian judicial authorities and the
international police for committing unlawful actions."
</P>
<P>
In addition to this, he said, after the judge made his
comments orally "we made it clear that the Berlin local
court, investigating the Mykonos file, was not impartial and
that the respective judge ignored the independence of the
judicial system and did not let the opposite side to enjoy
the right to defend."
</P>
<P>
The accusations leveled by the court against the Islamic
Republic of Iran lacked legal value and were rejected at the
same time, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Mykonos case was raised again weeks before senior
German Foreign Ministry officials were reportedly to visit Iran
next month to mend Bonn-Tehran relations strained by the case.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the German officials would also
discuss with Iranian officials the death sentence on the
German businessman Helmut Hofer on charges of having illegal
sexual relations with an Iranian Muslim woman.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel has warned that the
Bonn-Tehran relations would depend on Hofer's fate, though the
German government was ready to improve them.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran claimed that Hofer's case was tried
independently and according to the country's laws which ban
sexual relations between a Muslim woman and a non-Muslim man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Apologizes for Statement on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon had apologized to Jordan over his statement on
an assassination attempt against an Hamas leader in Jordan by
Israeli Agents last September.
</P>
<P>
The Semi-official Jordan Times Saturday quoted informed sources
as saying that Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent, had
received an "apology letter" from Sharon who said his statement on
the assasination of anti-Israeli Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) political bureau leader Khalid Mashaal were
"misunderstood."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two Jordanian Arabic dailies reported Friday that
Sharon wrote to Hassan that "what he wrote was misunderstood and
he did not mean to threaten the sovereignty of Jordan, its
integrity and its people."
</P>
<P>
Sharon told Israel's Channel Two television on March 14 that
Israel had informed Jordan before it decided to assassinate
Mashaal. Mashaal survived the assassination attempt by two agents
from Israeli overseas intelligence service Mossad in Amman.
</P>
<P>
The statements arose wide protests in Amman. On March 15,
acting Minister of Foreign Affairs Talal Sata'an Al-Hassan on
behalf of the government summoned Israeli Ambassador to Jordan
Odid Airan to inform him of Jordan's protest and rejection
of the statements.
</P>
<P>
Later the next day, Deputy Prime Minister for Services and
Minister of Information Abdullah Ensour denied Sharon's statement
saying that the Jordanian government knew nothing about Israel's
decision to kill Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
Two Mossad agents were arrested last year in Amman for
trying to kill Mashaal by injecting poisonous chemical into
his left ear before his office on September 23, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian-Israeli relations sharply deteriorated over the
botched assassination attempt on Mashaal. Hussein immediately
suspended cooperation in security matters with Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Mossad chief Danny Yatom resigned last month over a series
of failed operations in Jordan and Europe against Hamas, Iran
and Hizbollah of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Then the Jordanian-Israeli relations began to warm up as
official high-level contacts were resumed at the beginning of
March.
</P>
<P>
The development was suddenly interrupted by Sharon's remarks
which were made only four days after Hassan visit to Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is the second Arab country after Egypt that signed
peace treaty with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
