<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Vows to Fight Against Fundamentalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz has said that his government will wage every kind of
struggle against Islamic fundamentalism within the rules of law
and democracy.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz made the remarks late Friday night at his exclusive
interview with Turkey's private ATV in response to a statement
issued by Turkish Armed Forces earlier in the day, which attacked
Yilmaz's earlier remarks on the military.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz has reportedly said that "I did not order the army to
fight against fundamentalism. The military should tend to its own
business." The military can not impose its will on the government,
he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In its statement, the military pressured Yilmaz's government to
take harder measures against the Islamic fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
The statement said "no matter what position or task is
represented, no one...can display an attitude or make any
suggestion or comment that will discourage, confuse, weaken or
overshadow the determination of the Turkish Armed Forces to
struggle against separatist or fundamentalist activities that
target the country's security."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to ATV, Yilmaz said that there are a lot of people who
have the views of fundamentalism, adding that the views must be
cleared away within the framework of law and democracy.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports have said that the army was unhappy with
the government's handling of the Islamic fundamentalism, which
was considered by the army as one of the worst enemies of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish prime minister pointed out that "no one can bring
Turkey again into a trap of separation, darkness of fundamentalism
and backwardness of coup." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
