<HEADLINE> Uganda on Rinderpest Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has declared to control
cross border cattle movement and forced vaccination in its north
in face of rinderpest in southern Sudan, The New Vision reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Philip Ociba, commissioner for veterinary services, said the
measure is aimed at preventing the spread of the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
Uganda received the report about the outbreak of rinderpest in
Torit, southern Sudan, and cattle movement from Sudan to Agoro
Market in northern Uganda, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Hassan, the Sudanese Pan African rinderpest campaign
coordinator, confirmed the disease last month in Torit.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic is reportedly attributed to civil wars which had
hampered livestock vaccination.
</P>
<P>
Kezimbira Muyingo, State Minister for Agriculture, advised
businessmen earlier to intercept meat into Uganda without health
and veterinary marks and send it back to prevent the spread of
the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
