<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) drew some institutional support this week with
finance stocks attracting investors on expectation of more
development on mergers, pushing up the Composite Index.
</P>
<P>
The market this week started on a weak note in the absence of
fresh leads coupled with poor corporate earnings, but staged a
rebound from mid-week on optimism about the expected economic
stimulant to be announced by Deputy Prime Minister and Finance
Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Anwar is scheduled to speak in Parliament on Tuesday where he
is expected to reveal the revised forecast on the economic growth
besides spelling out more measures to stimulate the economy and to
strengthen the local currency -- the ringgit -- further, which
would boost investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
In the week, local institutionals were seen picking up selected
blue chips while foreign funds were also present although small in
numbers.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index closed the week 23.08 points higher at
731.24 as compared to 708.16 at the close last week.
</P>
<P>
The all Main Board Emas Index rose 6.20 points to 185.56 from
last week's close at 179.36, the Industrial Index gained 32.10
points to 1,307.87 from 1,275.77 last week and the second board
index rose 5.26 points to 185.21 from 179.95.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the main board turnover decreased to 1.022
billion shares valued at 2.594 billion ringgit (about 712.637
million U.S. dollars) from 1.023 billion shares worth 2.190
billion ringgit (about 601.648 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board volume declined to 109.982 million shares
valued at 280.501 million ringgit (about 77.06 million U.S.
dollars) from 118.446 million shares worth 293.371 million ringgit
(about 72.354 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Off-market turnover expanded to 59.387 million shares valued at
185.039 million ringgit (about 50.834 million U.S. dollars) from
31.108 million shares worth 173.356 million ringgit (about 47.625
million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
