<HEADLINE> Savimbi's Status Recognized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos issued a decree here Friday, acknowledging Jonas Savimbi
as head of the country's largest opposition party, the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Blondin Beye, United Nations special envoy to Angola, made the
announcement to the press on Friday night after his meeting with
Angolan Prime Minister Franca van-Dunem.
</P>
<P>
The move, said Beye, marks a step forward in the Angolan peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The envoy revealed that the new agenda for the peace process
has set aside deadlines for 12 tasks unaccomplished by the Lusaka
Peace Accord signed in 1994. Up to now, six has been completed.
</P>
<P>
Other tasks remaining to be done include the shift of UNITA
headquarters from central city of Bailundo to capital Luanda,
turning UNITA-controlled radio station into a commercial one,
placing Savimbi's guards on the national police list, appointing
UNITA members as ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
The deadline set for the tasks is April 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
