<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of Crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week lower
mostly in line with the strength of the local unit -- the ringgit
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The local unit regained its strength against the greenback as
it hovered around 3.64 at the close this week against a recovery
to 3.82 towards the end of last week.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market, there were some buying activities
on Thursday, but prices fell back on the following day as the
ringgit got stronger.
</P>
<P>
The "unsupportive" palm oil forecast by private crop forecaster
Ivan Wong also dampened sentiment, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Wong forecast that March 1998's palm oil production to increase
by five percent to 630,000 tons from 601,219 tons produced in
February.
</P>
<P>
However, he estimated palm oil stocks for March at 715,000 tons
against the Palm Oil Registration and Licensing Authority's
(PORLA's) figure at 736,670 tons in February.
</P>
<P>
March south ended the week 30 ringgit (about 8.24 U.S. dollars)
lower to 2,265 ringgit (about 622.25 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) was volatile with thin
volume this week due to the lack of buying interests, especially
from the European buyers.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover for the week decreased to 294 tons from
324 tons last week with the bulk of the transactions coming from
the local and Japanese buyers.
</P>
<P>
On the week's closing day Friday, players short-covered their
positions ahead of the weekend despite the continuous uptrend of
the ringgit against the greenback, saving price from falling
further.
</P>
<P>
Tin price ended 27 sen lower this week to 19.80 ringgit (about
5.43 U.S. dollars) per kg from 20.07 ringgit (about 5.51 U.S.
dollars) per kg at last week's close.
</P>
<P>
The premium between the KLTM and that of the London Metal
Exchange (LME) narrowed to 155 U.S. dollars per ton from 127 U.S.
dollars per ton last week.
</P>
<P>
This week, the Malaysian rubber market was choppy as most
buyers adopted a "wait-and-see-attitude" and the strengthening of
the ringgit against the US dollar since early this week also kept
players on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian rubber also faced stiff competition from the Thai and
Indonesian rubber which was offered at lower prices, forcing local
sellers to adjust downward their prices relative to their
competitors.
</P>
<P>
April RSS One closed the week 1.5 sen higher to 279.00 sen
(about 76.64 U.S. cents) per kg while SMR 20 slipped by 12.5 sen
to 271.50 sen (about 74.58 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for March 19 was at 191.00
Malaysia/Singapore cents per kg as against 200.59 cents on March
12.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average stood at 193.85 cents per kg
against 202.38 cents last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Mobilized to Prevent Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's police and military
forces have been mobilized to monitor forests as long drought
poses a threat of continued fires nation-wide, forestry officials
said saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, there have been 200 fires nation-wide,
damaging 4,700 hectares of forests.
</P>
<P>
The higher-than-average temperatures combined with drought have
resulted in drastically lower water levels in rivers, canals and
streams, and forests are now very dry.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's fire fighting capabilities have been improved with
the construction of meteorological stations, watch-towers,
reservoirs, canals and dams, and the purchase of new fire-fighting
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
