<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Bank Bosses Sacked in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
exercised the mandate as the major shareholder of the Kenya
Commercial Bank (KCB) in sacking KCB Executive Chairman Alexander
Kaminchia and General Manager Elijah arap Bii.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper East African Standard Saturday quoted Kenyan
Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae as saying in a statement Friday
that the government had appointed Peter Nyakiamo as the new KCB
executive chairman and Ernest Saino as the new general manager.
</P>
<P>
The sacking of the top bank bosses followed the firing of
three KCB directors Thursday who were involved in large amount of
unsecured and unserviced insiders' loans.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some KCB officials owed the bank large
unserviced loans amounting to more than 2.6 million U.S. Dollars
with Bii reportedly owing over 1.25 million Dollars and other two
directors owing 700,000 and 620,000 Dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
The KCB shares fell to a record low of 57 Kenyan Shillings
Friday at the Nairobi Stock Exchange and brokers said that this
was the lowest price in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has a 60 percent share-holding in KCB
which is the largest commercial bank in East Africa, and is
scheduled to sell a 25 percent stake in KCB next month.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the unsecured and unserviced loans of
KCB would have a negative impact on the government's plans to
offload share-holdings in the bank which has assets estimated at
73.5 billion Shillings (about 1.22 billion Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
