<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis:  Clinton's Visit to Unfold New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
imminent visit to six African countries, claimed to be one to
promote the continent's prosperity and stability, is actually an
opportunity to unfold Washington's new "partnership with Africa
into the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
The "partnership" relation with the whole sub-Saharan region
is clearly revealed in Clinton's itinerary of the visit, which
starts from March 22 and covers Ghana, Uganda, Senegal, Botswana,
South Africa and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
By including two countries in west Africa, two in the southern
region, and one each in east and central Africa, Clinton is
trying to give a touch of a geographical balance to his visit,
the first by a sitting U.S. president in two decades.
</P>
<P>
While Senegal is a clear signal showing United States'
intention to form partnership with African states which were once
considered part of France's sphere of influence, a two-hour stop
in Rwanda, which is later added to Clinton's African tour, is to
demonstrate U.S. concern over regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The thrust of U.S. "partnership" policy toward Africa is to be
undergirded by the Africa Growth and Opportunity Act of 1997 and
the Africa Crisis Response Force Initiative.
</P>
<P>
While the Act stresses Washington's interest in helping
sub-Saharan nations get onto the track of prosperity as claimed
by the U.S. government, the Initiative emphasizes the provision
of training and equipment, primarily communications gear, to
African countries to create interoperability among units from
different nations.
</P>
<P>
The Africa Growth and Opportunity Act, which is labeled by the
media as a U.S. "gift" to Africa, would, as Clinton said,
significantly broaden African countries' access to American
market, spur growth in the continent, and help the poorest
countries eliminate or reduce their bilateral debt, thus
assisting them in building a better life for their people.
</P>
<P>
The Act, announced on June 17 last year and passed at the
House of Representatives on March 11 just before Clinton's
historic African tour, would allow sub-Saharan countries to
export textiles and apparel to the U.S. in unlimited, duty-free
quantities.
</P>
<P>
Under the Africa Growth and Opportunity Act, Africa can ship
up to 1.3 billion Dollars' worth of textiles annually up to 2005,
thus offering an "entry point" to the U.S. market, and paving the
way for the continent to "move onto a higher level of
manufacturing and trade."
</P>
<P>
U.S. textile and apparel imports from sub-Saharan nations
currently total 350 million U.S. Dollars a year, even if imports
from the continent treble as a result of the legislation, they
would account for merely two percent of the 46-billion-Dollar
textile market in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatian President Meets Russian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Croatian President Franjo Tudjman
put forward again his proposal on demilitarization of Bosnia when
meeting Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the proposal, Tudjman noted that Bosnia's demilitarization
should be enforced under the guarantees of the international
community and through the signing of agreements with neighboring
Croatia and Yugoslavia safeguarding Bosnia's territorial integrity
and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman told Primakov it is very important to protect Bosnian
Croats who account for only 17.3 percent of the total population,
far less than Bosnian Serbs or Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, who came here for visit Friday, expressed "great
interest" in the proposal. He passed Tudjman an invitation from
Russian President Boris Yeltsin to visit Russia, which Tudjman
accepted with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
Primakov also met with his Croatian counterpart Mate Granic to
discuss bilateral relations, the situation in Bosnia and Kosovo
and issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Granic said Russia's role of keeping balance between Croatia
and Yugoslavia is welcome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
