<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Bricks Forbidden For Building In Shandong Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 21 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province is
expected to use fly-ash bricks instead of red bricks in a bid to
reduce air pollution and to protect farmland.
</P>
<P>
Lots of farmland has been destroyed and air is seriously
polluted every year because of the manufacture of red bricks in
this province, according to an official of Shandong's construction
department.
</P>
<P>
However, the amount of fly ash produced by thermal power plants
has increased to be several million tons a year, with an average
annual growth rate of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Using bricks made from fly ash instead of red bricks,
therefore, is a good method for improving farmland and improving
air quality, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Jinan, capital of the province, is expected to use fly-ash
bricks in all of its large buildings, the official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Clinton's Visit to Unfold New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kenya and Mauritius, however, were listed as countries
"unqualified' for the benefit, since both were found by the White
House as having failed to establish satisfactory safeguards
against trans-shipment to the U.S. of textiles and clothing made
in countries that remain subject to quotas and tariffs.
</P>
<P>
What's more important is that the two countries do not
willingly undergo structural adjustment programs in line with the
demand of Washington and some international organizations under
the U.S. influence.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have noted that the borrowing from the West and
international financial institutions, as well as bilateral aid
are, more often than not, in close connection with
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Some African economists also argue that the answer to Africa's
economic woes lie in the governments' giving up control of vital
corporations involved in agriculture, mining, insurance, banking,
fishing and everything.
</P>
<P>
It actually means that westerners could own controlling shares
of private industries and utilities in any African countries
receiving U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
This is like a fly-weight boxer contending with the champion
Holyfid. African countries, which have just started their
economic take-off, could be knocked out in the obviously unfair
fight.
</P>
<P>
The Africa Crisis Response Force Initiative, meanwhile, could
be interpreted as a military back-up for the economic benefits
U.S. is trying to seek from the continent.
</P>
<P>
The Initiative, launched in June 1996, is not aimed at the
establishment of a standing African army but to create a
"stand-by" peace-keeping capacity so that participant nations can
act in concert under United Nations auspices to prevent or
resolve conflicts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
But African observers find that the shift in U.S. military
policy in the continent is a new version of engagement with
Africa after its disaster in the peace-keeping effort in early
1990s in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The Crisis Response Force Initiative is actually a guarantee
for U.S. market scramble in Africa where regional conflicts and
civil wars are making peace and stability fragile, thus posing a
threat to development and more importantly, to U.S. investment on
the continent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that U.S. direct investment in the region at
the end of 1996 totaled 4.9 billion Dollars in book value terms,
up 30 percent from 1994. During 1992-96, the average annual
return on book value of U.S. direct investment in Africa was 28.7
percent, 2.5 times the rate of its return globally.
</P>
<P>
U.S. bilateral trade has also picked up rapidly, with its
exports to Africa in 1997 reaching 6.2 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Just as Clinton said before his African tour, a stronger,
stable and prosperous Africa will be a better economic partner, a
better partner for security and peace.
</P>
<P>
Washington's partnership with Africa, embodied in both the
Africa Growth and Opportunity Act and the Crisis Response Force
Initiative, is part of U.S. global strategy for a sustainable
development well into the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
