<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Takin Gives Birth to Baby in Beijing Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- A five-year-old takin has given
birth to a baby takin in Beijing endangered species protection
center.
</P>
<P>
The newborn takin is 50 centimeters long, weighing about 3
kilograms and with grey hair.
</P>
<P>
Both the mother and the father, a six-year-old takin, are from
the Qinling Mountains in northwest China. They have lived together
in the center for four years.
</P>
<P>
A takin is usually 1.8-to-2 meters long and 1.3-to-1.5 meters
high, weighing 250 to 300 kilograms. It is more like a sheep in
shape.
</P>
<P>
China has set up protection zones for takins, a goatlike bovid,
in the provinces of Sichuan, Shaanxi and Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 1,000 wild animals in 50 species in the
Beijing endangered species protection center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
