<HEADLINE> Cuba: End U.S. Sanctions Against Cuba Completely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Cuban State Council President
Fidel Castro said here Friday that the U.S. lifting of ban on
direct flights between the two countries is "positive and
constructive."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with CNN, Castro said that the measure will be
"helpful to a better climate for Cuban-U.S. relations." But he
added he needs to see the full details of the measure.
</P>
<P>
News from Washington reported that President Bill Clinton was
to announce Friday the lifting of ban on direct flights, the
permission of money remittances to relatives in Cuba by Cubans
living in U.S. and the easing of restrictions on U.S. medicine
sales to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cuban Foreign Ministry spokesman Alejandro Gonzalez
said the U.S. should completely give up its sanctions against Cuba
and abolish all its "evil and immoral policies."
</P>
<P>
Meeting U.N. human rights officials in Geneva on Friday, Cuban
Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina reiterated his opposition to
U.S. economic, financial and trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
Media here said that the U.S. lifting of ban constitutes only
"a drop of water in the desert," and the right thing the
U.S. should do is to fundamentally change its position on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Cuba estimates that the 40-year U.S. embargo has brought on it
an economic loss of 60 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
