<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Construct More Libraries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- China will build 50,000 new
libraries in the next 11 years, with the hope of achieving the
goal of "one township, one library", today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the country now has 2,676
libraries, with every county having just one.
</P>
<P>
The construction of grassroots libraries is part of the
Knowledge Project, a nationwide program that was launched last
year with financing from nine ministries and commissions.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the project will encourage the public to read
more," the newspaper quoted Du Ke, director of the Library Affairs
Department of the Ministry of Culture, as saying.
</P>
<P>
China published 19.3 billion copies of national and provincial
newspapers, 2.5 billion copies of magazines and 7.1 billion copies
of books last year.
</P>
<P>
It invested 800 million yuan in libraries in 1997, compared
with just 60 million yuan in 1980.
</P>
<P>
A US-based association of Chinese-American professors has also
carried out a scheme to build libraries in southwest China's
Yunnan, Guizhou provinces, and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
A dozen of Aihua (Love China) libraries have already been set up,
with 6,000 U.S. dollars of investment in each from the association
for purchase of books.
</P>
<P>
A China Readers' Association is expected to be founded later
this year, which will be put in charge of the implementation of
the projection.
</P>
<P>
Many provinces and cities have already set up their own
readers' associations, providing opportunities to buy books by
discount and information on new books.
</P>
<P>
Preparation is also under way for next year's national reading
activity to mark the return of Macao and the 50th anniversary of
the founding of New China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
