<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Sugar Production Crosses Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has produced 162,000
tons of sugar during the current fiscal year (starting from July
1, 1997) 17,000 tons more than the target, media reports said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Two sugar mills out of the total of 15 are still producing
sugar in full swing, and the output of sugar is expected to reach
170,000 tons by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
In the last fiscal year, this South Asian country's 15 sugar
mills produced 135,000 tons against their optimum production
capacity of 210,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Though the sugar production surpassed the target, 125,000 tons
of sugar would be imported this year to meet the total demand of
the country, the reports predicted.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Commerce and Industry Minister Tofael Ahmed has
asked the concerned authorities to monitor the sugar distribution
system in order not to let vested quarters create any crisis in
any part of the country, the reports added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
