<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Drug Center Changes Battle Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Northern Drug
Suppression and Prevention Center is once again adjusting its
strategy to combat narcotics smugglers.
</P>
<P>
Banpot Piamdee, the center's director, said intelligence
operations will be boosted to catch up with drug dealers who have
altered their tactics.
</P>
<P>
The new plan, to be put into practice, will involve local
police and soldiers in anti-drug operations, while anti-drug
officials will cooperate in terms of policy and intelligence, said
Banpot, quoted by today's Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
He said anti-drug officials who took part in past operations
will withdraw from such raids because they have their own work to
do.
</P>
<P>
These officials will train soldiers and police, and double
check information at the center, Banpot said.
</P>
<P>
He said the center will investigate cases of drug dealers --
be they government officials, politicians or law enforcement
officers.
</P>
<P>
In the latest five-month operation with the participation of
anti-drug officials, more than 100,000 amphetamine pills were
confiscated, said Banpot.
</P>
<P>
"We set up a lot of checkpoints and searched every vehicle. The
intensive search did have psychological effect," he said.
</P>
<P>
He voiced concern about the increasing number of people in the
illicit business, saying the sluggish economy would bring in new
faces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's First Gas Plant Goes into production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's first plant for
producing liquefied natural gas went into experimental production
last week, the Associated Press of Bangladesh (APB) reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The plant, named Koilashtila LPG (liquefied petroleum gas)
Fractionation Plant and situated in Sylhet 208 kilometers
northeast of here, was set up at a cost of 200 million taka (4.35
million U.S. dollars), and will be formally inaugurated sometime
in the next month.
</P>
<P>
The plant will annually produce 5,000 tons of liquefied gas by
fractionating natural gas supplied by the Gas Well No. 2 at
Koilashtila under the Sylhet Gasfield Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Initially, the plant will produce about 2,000 cylinders of LPG
daily, and its capacity will be increased by 50 percent in the
future, APB added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
