<HEADLINE> Zubak Backs Bosnia Non-Militarization Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Croatian Presidency of the
Republic of Bosnia Kresimir Zubak said Friday he supported
establishing Bosnia as a non-militarization zone, as proposed by
Croatian President Franjo Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
Zubak made the remarks in Sarajevo, capital of Bosnia during
talks with Mr A. Vershbowon, the United States ambassador to the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In a communique released by his office in Sarajevo, Zubak said
that judged from an economic point of view, the proposal deserved
much attention.
</P>
<P>
He said Bosnia needed money to rebuild its war-torn homeland,
and military appropriations were not allowed. Non-militarization
in Bosnia should not block Bosnia from further developing ties
with the NATO.
</P>
<P>
Vershbowon said Tudjman's proposal, made Thursday, was very
interesting. He said the suggestion could become one of the
prerequisites leading to a long stability in a wide area,
particularly in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
But a senior Bosnian official opposed the proposal. The
official said it would be very difficult to achieve the suggestion
because Bosnia was surrounded by military forces. Any
non-militarization in Bosnia would be like dropping a stone into
the sea, he added.
</P>
<P>
It was not possible for Bosnia to lose its military force and
join the NATO peace partnership program, the official said.
</P>
