<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Investors to be Treated as Nationals in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Investors from the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) are expected to be given treatment
similar to those of the nationals if they invest in the region,
the Bangkok Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Deputy Secretary-General of the Board of
Investment Chakramon Phasukvanich, who attended the recent meeting
of the Working Committee on ASEAN Investment.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, coming from the meeting held in Brunei, was aimed
to promote intra-ASEAN investment.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, ASEAN investors would be treated as locals
under each member nation's investment laws, Chakramon said.
</P>
<P>
According to Thai laws, for instance, joint ventures with
foreign investors require Thais to hold a minimum 51 percent
stake. As a result, ASEAN investors interested in launching
investment projects in Thailand would be given the same holding.
</P>
<P>
Chakramon said the proposal will be submitted to the committee
on international economic policy for approval soon and the
resolution will be forwarded to ASEAN economic ministers' meeting
to be held in may.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is part of the ASEAN investment area initiative.
At the unofficial ASEAN summit last December in Malaysia, the
ASEAN investment area was set to come into force in 2010. the
inflow of liberal investment in the area will be allowed in 2020.
</P>
<P>
Chakramon said under the initiative, ASEAN members would
cooperate in exchanging investment information, preparing data
based on investment, ensuring transparency in investment policies
and organizing intra-ASEAN investment promotion activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
