<HEADLINE> Special: Sea Turtle Population Threatened in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's sea turtle population
is facing a serious threat off the famous resort of Phuket Island
in southern Thailand from local fishermen, beach encroachment and
souvenir businesses, the Bangkok Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a turtle conservationist as saying that
sea turtles have indirectly been hit by cyanide poisoning that the
local fishermen used in catching lobsters.
</P>
<P>
The conservationist, Manop Kidsarng, said that many fishermen
sell turtle eggs to restaurants and dead turtles to craftsmen who
use their shells to make ornaments.
</P>
<P>
Property development, which also brought waste water and
pollution to the beaches, was also discouraging sea turtles from
coming ashore to lay eggs, he added.
</P>
<P>
Local conservation groups have been collecting sea turtle eggs,
hatching them and releasing baby turtles back into the sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
