<HEADLINE> Chuan Government Survives No-Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government Saturday
morning weathered the first political storm by winning the
no-confidence vote launched by the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
At Saturday's voting in the 393-strong house of
representatives, some 208 legislators voted for the government
while 177 against with two abstentions. Some 387 legislators took
part in the voting.
</P>
<P>
The voting came after a three-day no-confidence debate, during
which the opposition focused the attacks on the government's
mismanagement, abusing of power and suspected corruption by some
cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai vowed that he
will not reshuffle the cabinet after the no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
The no-confidence motion is the first of its kind launched by
the opposition parties since Chuan's eight-party coalition took
office in last November after the economic crisis forced the
former prime minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh to resign. 
</P>
