<HEADLINE> U.S. Steel Imports Continue to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 20 (Xinhua) -- United States steel imports went
up 19.8 percent in January over December 1997, to reach 2.52
million tons, the American Institute for International Steel
(AIIS) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The AIIS president, Horst E. Buetle, said: "The same strong
steel demand that pushed U.S. imports to their highest level in
1997 continued through the first month of 1998."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imported a record volume of 31.20 million tons in
1997, breaking the previous record of 30.10 million tons in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, the import volume in January was 19.8 percent less
than that of the same month in 1997, when import shipments were
driven especially high by repeated price-hike warnings by
U.S. producers, the president said.
</P>
<P>
"So far, the Asian financial crisis does not appear to have
resulted in a surge of imports from that region," Buelte said.
</P>
<P>
"Of the major steel producers, only Japan showed an increase in
shipments to the U.S. in January," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
