<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Impose 5 Percent tax on Foreign Buying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAkARTA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
impose a new 5 percent tax on the gross value of foreign exchange
purchases by individuals or legal entities in a bid to reduce
speculation in the country, a spokesman of the Finance Ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
Agus Haryanto said here Friday night that the speculation on
foreign exchange had resulted in the weakening of the rupiah
(national currency), so the government will impose the new tax
from next Monday (March 23).
</P>
<P>
The tax is classified as an income tax, he said, and as such
the amount paid by a taxpayer when purchasing a foreign exchange
could be credited to his annual tax return.
</P>
<P>
He said there would also be no tax on foreign currency
purchases made by banks and authorized money changers.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the new ruling is expected to hurt
travelers planning to go abroad, as well as those intending to
study overseas.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the government also raised the departure tax
from 250,000 rupiah to 1,000,000 rupiah per person. 
</P>
</TEXT>
