<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Way Paved for U.S.-China Nuclear Cooperation: U.S. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- A senior United States
official said here Friday that the U.S.-China agreement on nuclear
cooperation has paved the way for American companies to compete
against their counterparts in the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Sandra Kristoff, special assistant to the president and senior
director for Asian programs at the National Security Council, told
reporters that the accord, signed in 1985, came into effect after
Congress failed to respond to President Bill Clinton's
certification before the deadline of March 18.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton certified on January 12 that China had stuck
to its commitment to non-proliferation. He was obliged to do so
before the pact went into effect, but Congress had only 30 days to
deliberate. Only two-thirds of the votes in both Houses could turn
down the president's certification.
</P>
<P>
"I think that you will see American companies like Westinghouse
and GE begin in earnest to bid on nuclear projects in China,"
Kristoff said, defending the president from critics' protests.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a group of congressmen signed a letter
Friday to Clinton, urging the president to maintain the sanctions
against China -- because of their suspicion about China's
sincerity in carrying out its commitment.
</P>
<P>
Kristoff said: "From the administration's point of view, we
would hope that American companies would be as competitive, and in
fact I believe they are as competitive, as some of the other
nuclear suppliers in the world, like France."
</P>
<P>
Because of the delay in implementing the U.S.-China nuclear
cooperation agreement, the American companies lost their edge over
counterparts in past years. They hoped for billions of U.S.
dollars in business if the accord with China passed Congress.
</P>
<P>
The official said the accord was part of the sanctions waived
so far by the Administration. The U.S. imposed the sanctions on
China following the turbulence in Beijing in 1989.
</P>
<P>
"We have waived a number of them. We would be in a position to
look at peeling away these sanctions one by one as there is
progress in the U.S.-China relationship," Kristoff said.
</P>
<P>
She confirmed the recent press report that Washington would
loosen export controls on satellite launches for China.
</P>
<P>
"Satellite launches is one of these where we have, the
president has on a number of occasions issued national interest
waivers," she noted.
</P>
<P>
On Clinton's trip to China scheduled for late June, Kristoff
said: "You are going to see us working hard over the next 90 days
with Beijing to try to produce some results on areas like
non-proliferation."
</P>
<P>
Military-to-military discussions, maritime cooperation, rule of
law, law enforcement and human rights were issues to be discussed
between the two countries in order to make President Clinton's
trip to China a success, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
