<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN to Finance Plan for Aiding China's Rural Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- China and the United Nations Fund
for Population Activities (UNFPA) will jointly launch a program
next month focusing on improving reproductive health and family
control in rural China, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 32 counties in 22 provinces, many of which are
populous areas in central and western China, will be included in
the project, scheduled to be completed by 2000, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, UNFPA will grant 14 million
U.S. dollars to finance the project.
</P>
<P>
The joint project is one of the China's responses to the
Program of Action of the International Conference on Population
and Development (ICPD) that was held in Cairo of Egypt in 1994,
the newspaper quoted an official with the State Family Planning
Commission as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ICPD program calls upon all nations to provide high quality
reproductive health services for couples of reproductive age and
to integrate family planning activities with information on
preventing sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
A reproductive health service system in China's selected
counties is expected to satisfy the public's need for both
knowledge and health care.
</P>
<P>
Training will also be organized to improve local family
planning and health workers' professional skills, and sex
education will be available for teenagers.
</P>
<P>
Five kinds of contraceptives will be provided for couples of
reproductive age to choose from. And practical methods for
reproductive health and family planning promotion will be spread
to the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
The State Family Planning Commission has also set up a
three-year project (1998-2000) with the Human Reproductive Program
under the World Health Organization (WHO) to support China's
development of new types of contraceptives and carry out training
for professionals.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese commission is selecting some possible subjects from
across the country to invite international cooperation in the
field of reproductive health care and family planning, said the
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
