<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi To Adopt Contract System When Employing Sri </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has agreed to follow
the streamlined contract system when employing Sri Lankans with
effect from May this year, the official Daily News reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Labor Minister John Seneviratne who returned to the
country Friday from a successful one-week tour of Saudi Arabia and
 Kuwait told the paper that Saudi Arabia had taken this decision
after being briefed about the benefits of the new contract system.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said that to ensure the welfare of Sri Lankans,
particularly housemaids, the new contract system has been
introduced since last November on the initiative of the Sri Lankan
government.
</P>
<P>
The new contract system is a binding document, providing that
the Sri Lankan Mission in the respective country could intervene
for the benefit of the employee in the case of non-payment of
salaries and violations of the contract on the part of employer.
</P>
<P>
Almost all Middle East countries where Sri Lankans are employed
have accepted the contract system with the exception of Saudi
Arabia, the Minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the United Arab Emirates where around 125,000 Sri Lankans
are employed, including 60,000 housemaids and 40,000 garment
workers, it was agreed that to resolve the issue of non-payment of
salaries by the employer, bank guarantees would be provided to Sri
Lankan expatriate workers ensuring payment of two months'
salaries.
</P>
<P>
His successful visit to Saudi Arabia would be helpful to ensure
the greater welfare of Sri Lankans working in the Middle East and
therefore to boost the country's foreign exchange earnings, the
Minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
