<HEADLINE> At Least 13 Killed by Georgia Tornado </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- A sudden tornado struck the
northern part of the United States' state of Georgia Friday
morning killing at least 13 people, injuring more than 90 others
and destroying mobile homes and schools.
</P>
<P>
The tornado carved a 16-kilometer trail of destruction through
Georgia after it touched down at about 6:30 a.m. EST (1130 GMT) in
northern Gainesville, about 80 kilometers north of Atlanta. It
left more than 12,000 people without power, reports from Atlanta
said.
</P>
<P>
The storm touched down just outside Lanier Elementary School in
Hall County, destroying the building. It picked up a produce truck
full of tomatoes and onions and hurled it through the air into a
house, killing the driver.
</P>
<P>
Among the dead were four children killed when a mobile house
was leveled and another child and an adult, who were found in a
pond where they had been dumped by the funnel of wind.
</P>
<P>
The dead also included a sheriff's deputy who was hit by a car
when she stepped out of her vehicle to help another driver whose
car had been hit by a falling tree.
</P>
<P>
Georgia Governor Zell Miller, who flew over the scene in a
helicopter to get a first-hand look at the wreckage, said it was
"horrible". In some areas, there was nothing left except the
cement of driveways.
</P>
<P>
Miller declared a state of emergency in Hall, White, Dawson,
Habersham and Rabun counties.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton granted federal disaster relief within
hours.
</P>
<P>
About 200 people were killed when a tornado struck Hall County
in April 1936. 
</P>
</TEXT>
