<HEADLINE> Coal Province Strives to Convert to Electricity Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Shanxi, China's richest province
in coal, is striving to generate more electricity to sell to
neighboring provinces rather than selling coal.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year the province had a total installed
capacity of nearly 10 million kilowatts (kw), turning out 54.5
billion kwh and diverting 10 billion kwh to the rest of the
country in the year.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhensheng, director of the provincial power industry bureau,
said the province is building a 2.1 million-kw power plant for
east China's Jiangsu Province, scheduled for completion in
2000. Meanwhile, it is preparing to build three more power plants
for Shandong and Hebei provinces, as well as the city of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The director estimated that the province, which borders Inner
Mongolia in north China, will see its newly added installation
increase by 1 million kw a year in three years, getting more
profits through selling electricity to other regions, whose
development is restricted by power shortages.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China and north China's Inner Mongolia are also major
contributors of electricity for the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
