<HEADLINE> Olympic Runner-up Wins 1,000m World Cup Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Olympic silver medalist Chris
Witty won her 1,000 meters World Cup speedskating title in track
record in West Allis, Wisconsin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
American Witty, world record-holder of 1 minute 15.43 seconds,
was timed in 1:17.41, breaking the track record of 1:18.74 she set
in January.
</P>
<P>
Canadians Catriona Lemay-Doan and Sylvian Bouchard won the
500-meter races as Nagano Olympic champion Lemay-Doan clocked
38.29 in the women's race and Bouchard timed in 35.98.
</P>
<P>
Adne Sondral of Norway skated 1:11.74 to win the men's 1,000m
title, shattering the track record of 1:12.76 set by Japan's
Manubo Horii last year.
</P>
<P>
The records fell in all four races was a sign of how much clap
skates have lowered times.
</P>
<P>
The Canadians dominated the 500 races, as Susan Auch finished
second in the women's event and Canadians took the top four spots
in the men's race.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian men also did well in the men's 1,000 as Bouchard
was second and Ireland was third. 
</P>
