<HEADLINE> Beijing to Treat More Waste Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will double its sewage
treatment capacity by the end of 1999, when the second phase of
construction of the city's biggest sewage plant is completed,
reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
From that date, Beijing will treat 42 percent of its waste
water, up from the current 21 percent, said Wang Changjing, an
official in charge of water resources management with the
municipal environmental protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
The first phase construction of the Gaobeidian water treatment
plant started in 1990, and upon completion in 1993, it took on 95
percent of the city's treatment work -- 2.5 million tons of sewage
per day.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has plans for 16 sewage plants by the end of 2010,
treating over 80 percent of waste water, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Water coming out of the Gaobeidian plant will be clean enough
to be discharged into the river. Experts are discussing the
further processing of water for use in factories, thus helping
alleviate the water shortage in Beijing, said Guan Long, vice
manager of Beijing No. 4 Municipal Engineering Co., which is
taking charge of the project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
