<HEADLINE> Brazil Makes Big Efforts to Reduce Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's National Bank of
Economic and Social Development (BNDESB) decided Friday to invest
12 million U.S. dollars in the Solidary Literacy Promotion Program
to reduce illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
The money will enable 100,000 illiterate people from 100
illiteracy-ridden cities learn to read and write.
</P>
<P>
The education program, launched in 1996, aims to foster a
national campaign to combat illiteracy, while creating more jobs
and improving work force quality.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 75,000 people from north and northeast Brazil, where
the illiteracy rate exceeded 47 percent, got an opportunity to
learn under the program.
</P>
<P>
Brazil currently ranks second on the illiteracy list for Latin
America, with 20 million illiterates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
