<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Throwing Seedlings in Sowing Rice Works Well in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The method of throwing instead
of the traditional practice of transplanting seedlings in sowing
rice has been gaining momentum in China's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Southern Guangdong Province is an example. Last year, it used
the throwing technique on nearly one million hectares of paddy
fields, accounting for one-third of the national total.
</P>
<P>
The high-yield planting technique, imported in the early 1990s,
requires growers to throw seedlings down into paddy fields,
standing on field banks.
</P>
<P>
The technique has been expanded to more than 3 million hectares
nationwide, making up 10 percent of the total paddy fields and
increasing more than one million tons of rice annually.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, for instance, harvested 450 kilograms more rice per
hectare in 1992 by using the new method, and saved approximately
half the production cost.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the province spread the use of the
technique on a total of 1.66 million hectares to increase 670,000
tons of rice output and 3.1 billion yuan in profit, and to save
2.11 billion yuan in production costs.
</P>
<P>
It plans to use the technique on 1.2 million hectares of paddy
fields this year, according to the provincial Agriculture
Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0191 </DOCNO>
