<HEADLINE> Feature: Expatriate Civil Servant Sees Posthandover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, in Siegel's eyes, something has become different after
the handover. In October 1997, he attended a regional conference
of Director General of Civil Aviation, where for the first time he
sat under the Bauhinia flag, the regional flag of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
In November 1997, He took part in the Conference on
Airworthiness of the International Civil Aviation Organization
(ICAO) in Montreal, for the first time as a member of the Chinese
delegation. Hong Kong used to join the British delegation on the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
"I was given a very warm welcome by the Chinese delegation to
the ICAO," he said, "They were very helpful and friendly, and give
me great assistance."
</P>
<P>
"Under the British delegation, I sat right at the back of the
hall; under the Chinese delegation, I sat right in the front of
the hall," said the Hong Kong official, "you see, they (Chinese)
change my position in the hall."
</P>
<P>
Besides the arrangement of sitting, he was impressed by another
aspect. "We're given more latitude under China this time than we
worked under the British," he explained, "we have established a
clear mechanism for communications with the Chinese in the
mainland, and the mechanism works well."
</P>
<P>
Sitting in his 46th-floor office where commands a good view of
the -glass-glazed skyscrapers in Central, Siegel said: "When I
look outside this window, I see what is stated in the Basic Law
and in the Joint Declaration is what has happened. "
</P>
<P>
"'Hong Kong people ruling Hong Kong' and 'a high degree of
autonomy' work very well. The concept of "one country, two
systems" has gone onto a good start. If it continues, the
prosperity of Hong Kong will be ensured," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
His confidence in the future of Hong Kong was built upon his
25-year connection with this Chinese city. When he arrived in
early 1970's, he did not intend to stay this long in Hong Kong,
but after he had been for a while, he fell in love with the Kai
Tak Airport, the people and the city.
</P>
<P>
Kai Tak is where he began his career and life in Hong Kong.
Starting from the passenger terminal, he later took the position
of the Airport General Manager for ten years through the 80s, in
his words, a very challenging time of rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, Kai Tak will be closed with the opening of
the New Airport at Chek Lap Kok. Siegel said: "I have mixed
feelings. Kai Tak is like your grandma. It is a wonderful good
lady. It serves so long so well."
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that Hong Kong needs a new airport with more
capacity, and Chek Lap Kok is the future of aviation in Hong Kong.
"I'll be sad to see it (Kai Tak) go, and I'll be glad to turn the
light down," said the man, who called himself an aviation man.
</P>
<P>
"I have always been proud to have been part of the city, even
in the future wherever I go and wherever I am," said Siegel, who
is expected to retire in six years.
</P>
<P>
He decided to stay in 1970's because he was motivated by a
"can do" spirit in Hong Kong. The city is so unique that "if it
can be done anywhere in the world, it can be done here", and the
people are vibrant, positive and hard working.
</P>
<P>
During the Sino-British negotiations in the 1980's, again, he
decided to stay on to transition. "Because I believe in the future
of Hong Kong and I have faith in the people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
