<HEADLINE> Hungary, Romania Agree on Joint Peace-keeping Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Hungary and Romania signed an
agreement here on Friday to establish a joint peace-keeping force
for the European region.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached by Hungarian Defense Minister Keleti
Gyorgy and his Romanian counterpart, Constantin Dudu Lonescu, said
that each of the countries would provide a maximum of 500 troops.
</P>
<P>
The proposed joint force would be charged with peace-keeping
and supplying humanitarian aid within the territory of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will go into effect 60 days after it is ratified
by the parliaments of the two countries. 
</P>
