<HEADLINE> U.S., Central America Strengthen Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The countries of Central
America, the Dominican Republic and the United States have further
developed their economic ties by signing an agreement to establish
a commerce and investment regional council here.
</P>
<P>
The council will intensify the integration among the countries
and consolidate economic relations to eventually eliminate the
trade barriers between the countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord signed Friday, economic cooperation among the
countries will be intensified. They have traditionally been
characterized by close ties of friendship and cooperation, Costa
Rican Foreign Trade Minister Jose Manuel Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement gives "the operative framework for a series of
commercial, investment and promotion actions in the private
sectors," he said.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Central America and the United States,
which is Central America's largest trading partner, represents
more than 50 percent of the total volume of the Central American
countries' exports and imports.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is one of the results of the presidential summit
involving the United States, Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala,
Honduras, and the Dominican Republic held in San Jose last May.
</P>
<P>
At this summit, the heads of state committed themselves to
promoting a bigger integration in the area and to forming a
commerce and investment regional council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
