<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, March 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government announced a plan Friday to
draw private investment into the infrastructure of London's
underground network.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott told the House of Commons
that private firms were to be given a role in running London's
Tube, although this was not privatization of the system and its
assets would remain in the public sector. (UK-Tube-Privatization)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- China favors a peaceful solution to the
Lockerbie case, including legal procedures, Qin Huasun, Chinese
ambassador to the United Nations, stressed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Qin also stressed that China is opposed to terrorism in any
form and is of the view that terrorists should be brought to
justice.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin made the remarks at the the meeting of the
Security Council, which held an open debate on the question of
Libya. (UN-China-Lockerbie Case)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- At least seven people were killed and 70 others
injured in an apparent tornado that tore through northern
Gainesville, Georgia, Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The storm also damaged homes, farm buildings and an elementary
school, and left more than 12,000 people without power, the
Associated Press reported. (US-Storm)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece Friday expressed its willingness to sign a
non-aggression pact with neighboring Turkey as part of its efforts
to improve the strained relations between the two countries for
decades.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that the Greek government was very favorable
towards the signing of a non-aggression pact with Turkey as long
as this accord would not be contrary to international law and
international treaties governing the status quo in the
region. (Greece-Turkey)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's Special Advisor
Diego Cordovez Friday conveyed a letter from Annan to Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides, hoping the bicommunal peace talks on
the island are to be resumed as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Cordovez after his meeting with Clerides,
during which they discussed the issue of resumption of Cyprus
peace talks which went into deadlock following two rounds of
bicommunal talks last summer. (Cyprus-U.N. Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Friday called on
the parties concerned in Angola to complete immediately and
without conditions the implementation of all remaining obligations
under the Lusaka Protocol and relevant Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimously adopted resolution, the Security Council
stressed the urgent need for the Government of Unity and National
Reconciliation of Angola (GURN) and in particular the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) to take
measures to move the peace process forward. (UN-Angola-Resolution)
</P>
