<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Leaders Call for New Forms of German-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Several German leaders joined a
chorus on Friday to stress the need to develop new forms of
German-U.S. relations in the post-Cold-War era.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a German-U.S. symposium titled "New Traditions" in
Berlin, German President Roman Herzog said that the German-U.S.
cooperation and friendship had helped to achieve wonders in the
past 40 years, including the end of the Cold War. Now there was a
need to bring about new wonders.
</P>
<P>
"We need more cooperation than in the past, but above all, we
need new forms of cooperation," Herzog said.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the symposium, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
announced that U.S. President Bill Clinton was due to pay a visit
to Berlin this May on the occasion of the 50th anniversary of the
U.S.-led 462-day airlift to the then West Berlin which was cut
from energy and food supplies from East Berlin and other
Soviet-occupied zone in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also noted that after its reunification in 1990, people
were expecting Germany to take more responsibility worldwide than
before and it was also ready to meet such expectations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel complained at
the meeting that Americans sometimes tended to underestimate the
contributions made by its European partners in the post-Cold-War
era and did not appreciate Europe's present developments in their
full dimensions.
</P>
<P>
"We Europeans want U.S. leadership, yes, but in partnership
with us," Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
A similar view was also voiced by the parliamentary group
leader of Kohl's ruling Christian Democratic Union party, Wolfgang
Schaeuble, who said that the European Union could only take bigger
political responsibility when it could participate in
decision-making along with the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
