<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Suggests US Air Force Limit B-2 Fleet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- An independent panel has
suggested that the U.S. Air Force limit its fleet of the costly
B-2 stealth bombers to the planned 21 planes, the Pentagon said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The panel, formed on orders from Congress and headed by former
Air Force Chief of Staff Larry Welch, said after a study that the
military should spend money on upgrading and extending the life of
the whole U.S. force of B-1, B-2 and B-52 bombers, rather than buy
more B-2s.
</P>
<P>
The nine-member group completed its study this week and sent
its report to the White House and Congress. The Pentagon plans to
buy 21 of the batwing, four-engine B-2s, but some lawmakers have
pressed to increase the number of the 2-billion-dollar B-2s.
</P>
<P>
As the Cold War is over, the U.S. Air Force is facing the
problem of new missions for its heavy bombers and the B-2 fleet
has been modified to carry large numbers of conventional cruise
missiles and bombs on international attack missions.
</P>
<P>
The panel recommended that 331 million U.S. dollars in extra
funds appropriated by Congress for the B-2 fleet in fiscal 1998 be
used for the planned baseline program.
</P>
<P>
The panel also recommended that the Pentagon better exploit the
potential of the current B-1, B-2 and B-52 force through more
operational attention and additional investment in support and
upgrades, the Pentagon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Puts off Vote on NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott on Friday indefinitely postponed a Senate vote on the
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), which
had been scheduled sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
Lott said the NATO enlargement would move behind other more
urgent items on the agenda, adding that it might not come to a
Senate vote until after the two-week recess in April.
</P>
<P>
"We have not received cooperation on any bill that's come up
this year, and I can only do so much to try to get the Senate to
focus and complete action and if they don't I have to turn to
other emergency matters," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I do have members on both sides of the aisle urging me to
delay it," Lott said.
</P>
<P>
"Until the Senate indicates a willingness to stay focused and
we get a little cooperation and don't have to have a filibuster
fight and cloture vote on every bill, then it will just have to
come up later," Lott said of NATO.
</P>
<P>
Lott said the Senate would move on Monday to consider an
emergency supplemental appropriation to pay for troop deployments
in Bosnia and the Gulf and for disaster relief, and would attempt
again on Tuesday to cut off debate on the education bill.
</P>
<P>
Lott's decision came as U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday made
a renewed pitch for the Senate to approve the alliance's
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arranged a ceremony attended by top national security
aides, military leaders and key senators at the White House to
appeal for the approval.
</P>
<P>
"The admission of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic will
be a very important milestone in building the kind of world we
want for the 21st century," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"A final decision is at hand," He said, stressing the vote
would be an historic affirmation of the United States' commitment
to Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
