<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Easing of Sanctions Against Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
announced on Friday that the U.S. will permit a resumption of
direct humanitarian charter flights to Cuba as part of measures
easing sanctions against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The actions that the U.S. administration will take also include
bipartisan legislation to meet humanitarian food needs in Cuba,
streamline the issuance of licenses for the sale of medical
supplies and permit Cuban Americans to send remittances to their
relatives in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"They do not reflect a change in policy towards the Cuban
government," said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
She added that economic pressure through the embargo and the
Helms-Burton Act will be maintained.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.'s embargo against Cuba has lasted nearly four
decades. In 1996, the Helms-Burton Act was enacted to punish any
foreign firms doing business with Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
