<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Transport Workers End Week-Long Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 20 (Xinhua) -- South African transport
workers ended their week-long strike on Friday after a compromise
over wages was reached.
</P>
<P>
The compromise over wage raise between employers and unions
was successfully brokered by the Commission for Conciliation,
Mediation and Arbitration.
</P>
<P>
Emily Fourie, spokeswoman for the Professional Transport
Workers' Union, said that the workers on strike were satisfied
with the wage increases agreed upon and would all be back at work
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The agreed increase were not as high as the workers would
have wanted, but in the end they were all very happy that there
had been an amicable resolution of the dispute." said Fourie.
</P>
<P>
She said that "Having lost their wages for the week they were
on strike, most of the strikers were relieved that they could now
go back to work and get on with their livings. "
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the wages for category five
workers or ultra-heavy duty drivers would get an 11.8 percent
increase, while lower level workers would receive increments of
up to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other workers such as clerks and secretaries, who previously
were not included in negotiations, would get an eight percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
The five-day strike by the 40,000 workers began on Monday
after their demand for a 14-percent wage increase across the
board was rejected by the Road Freight Employers' Association.
</P>
<P>
The workers demanded a 40-Rand (one US dollar equals five
Rand) wage increase for grade one workers instead of the 35
offered by employers, and a 60-Rand increase for grades four and
five instead of 54 Rand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Altitude May be Harmful to Some Infants: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Some infants may be put at high
risk if they fly on aircraft or stay at high altitude because of
the reduction in oxygen supply, British researchers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
David Southall and colleagues at North Staffordshire Hospital
Centre, Stoke on Trent, exposed 34 infants to air containing 15
percent oxygen, six percent less than the normal supply.
</P>
<P>
They found that four of the babies suffered a severe fall in
blood oxygen level although in the other cases, blood oxygen
levels were maintained at slightly reduced rates than normal.
</P>
<P>
"Exposure to airway hypoxia (poor oxygen supply) similar to
that experienced during air travel or on holidays at high altitude
may be harmful to some infants." researchers wrote in the British
Medical Journal.
</P>
<P>
The authors concluded that their findings may explain why some
infants, with reduced oxygen in their airways as a result of
respiratory infection, develop sudden or persistent falls in blood
oxygen saturation.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested that their study may contribute to
understanding the relation between respiratory infection, airway
hypoxia and sudden infant death syndrome.
</P>
<P>
The researchers carried out their study after two sets of
parents said they had lost their babies through cot deaths after
intercontinental flights.
</P>
<P>
One infant had died between 14 and 19 hours after a flight, and
the other between 40 and 41 hours later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980321.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Senate to Ratify NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday made a renewed pitch for the Senate to approve the
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) next
year into Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
As the Senate moves to vote on the alliance's expansion next
week, Clinton arranged a ceremony attended by top national
security aides, military leaders and key senators at the White
House to appeal for the approval.
</P>
<P>
"The admission of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic will
be a very important milestone in building the kind of world we
want for the 21st century," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"A final decision is at hand," He said, stressing the vote
would be an historic affirmation of the United States' commitment
to Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We can bring Europe together not by force of arms but by
possibilities of peace," Clinton declared. "That is the promise of
this moment, and we must seize it."
</P>
<P>
Some senators are urging that the legislation include a
provision that would stop, at least temporarily, additional new
members after Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic get in.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said this would be a mistake and contrary to the
alliance's values.
</P>
<P>
"It would fracture NATO's open door consensus," Clinton said,
adding it would create a dividing line in Europe at least
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
The president reiterated that the expansion of NATO will make
the alliances stronger, the America safer and Europe more stable
and united.
</P>
<P>
However, critics of the move contend an expanded NATO could
entangle the United States in a series of Bosnia-style
peacekeeping missions, poison relations with Russia and promote
instability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 16-member NATO decided last July to accept
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic as new members by 1999 and
signed accession protocols in December.
</P>
<P>
The documents have to be ratified by all the 16 parliaments and
so far only Canada, Denmark and Norway have ratified them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
