<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's Military Lashes out at Yilmaz' Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Armed Forces issued a
statement Friday, attacking Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz's remarks
against the military.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued after a meeting between Chief of
General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi and other armed forces leaders
to discuss the latest controversy between Yilmaz and the military
over the crack down on Islamic fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that the army was unhappy with the
government's handling of the Islamic fundamentalism, which was
considered by the army as one of the worst enemies of the country.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz reportedly said that "I didn't order the army to fight
against fundamentalism. The military should tend to its own
business." The military cannot impose its will on the government,
he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The military is pressuring Yilmaz' eight-month-old government
to take harder line against Islamic radicalism.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "no matter what position or task is
represented, no one ... can display an attitude or make any
suggestion or comment that will discourage, confuse, weaken or
overshadow the determination of the Turkish Armed Forces to
struggle against separatist or fundamentalist activities that
target the country's security."
</P>
<P>
It added that the military did not constitute a threat to the
country and has not acted in any manner that would shake the
nation's confidence.
</P>
<P>
"The fight against terrorism and Islamic fundamentalism is the
duty of everyone in this country who wants to live freely and
independently," the statement added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
